<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia-NATO Accord Could Be Signed on May 27: Primakov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeni
Primakov said here today that Russia could sign a treaty on
bilateral relations with the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) on May 27 in Paris.
</P>
<P>
"President Chirac has suggested that this document be signed on
May 27 in Paris. I am entitled by President Boris Yeltsin to say
that if the document was ready, he could come to Paris to sign
this document on the level of the leaders of Russia and the 16
member countries of NATO," said Primakov after holding talks with
President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
NATO and Russia are now negotiating a joint document with both
of them having the intention of signing it before the NATO Madrid
summit to be held on July 8-9, which will decide on which
countries will join the Western military alliance in the first
wave of its expansion.
</P>
<P>
The document is aimed at reducing Russian hostility toward
NATO's eastward expansion plan, which Moscow regards as a threat
to its national security.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, French Foreign Minister Herve de Charette said today
that Russia and NATO could find a "reasonable compromise" to reach
an agreement before the NATO Madrid summit.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that a reasonable compromise, the kind which
will take into account the worries of Russia, can be found before
the Madrid summit," said de Charette during a dinner given in
honor of Primakov in the French Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
De Charette also announced during the toast that French
President Jacques Chirac will visit Russia again on September
25-27, which he said will make up an "essential rod" of
Franco-Russian dialogue.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Primakov said during a toast at the dinner that
Russia considers NATO's eastward expansion plan "a grave error."
</P>
<P>
Primakov, who is on a two-day visit here, said Tuesday that
many questions remain to be solved between Russia and NATO before
a bilateral agreement can be signed.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia is opposed to the permanent deployment of
NATO military infrastructure and troops in the countries to be
newly absorbed by NATO: Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
