<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian President Appoints New Aide, Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today appointed a new aide on international affairs and two
ministers.
</P>
<P>
Sergei Yastrzhembsky, former deputy director of the President's
Office and Presidential press secretary, was appointed assistant
on international affairs to the President, to replace Dmitry
Ryurikov who was removed from the post over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Vice Prime Minister Oleg Sysuyev, appointed to the post on
March 17, said today that he had agreed to be the Minister of
Labor and Social Development at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Former Minister of Labor and Social Development Gennady
Melikyan resigned in late March.
</P>
<P>
Sysuyev, who is in charge of culture, public health and
education in the cabinet, said a panel would be set up in his
ministry to decide the country's basic direction on social reforms.
</P>
<P>
The president also relieved Poetr Rodionov of his ministerial
duties in the Ministry of Fuel and Power today.
</P>
<P>
Newspaper reports here said Rodionov submitted his resignation
last week after refusing to soften his disagreement with some new
government leaders on oil and natural gas reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
