<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal to Coordinate Sub-Regional Cooperation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Nepal has been entrusted with
the overall responsibility to coordinate the proposed four-nation
sub-regional cooperation in South Asia, the official news agency
RSS said today.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of Bangladesh, India and Nepal and the
Bhutanese ambassador to India met in New Delhi Tuesday to move
ahead the concept of the sub-regional cooperation between the four
countries, the RSS reported.
</P>
<P>
They agreed at the meeting that the first-phase studies on
possible cooperation projects will be launched in July 1997 and
completed within one year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers, who were attending the 12th Non-Aligned
Movement (NAM) Foreign Ministers' Conference in the Indian
capital, also agreed to assign respective coordinating
responsibilities to each of the countries, with Bhutan for the
studies on environment, Bangladesh for natural resources and
energy, India for trade and investment and Nepal for tourism,
multimodal transportation and communications.
</P>
<P>
The four South Asian countries earlier this month worked out a
framework of the sub-regional cooperation at a foreign secretary
level meeting here.  
</P>
</TEXT>
