<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finnish PM: Helsinki Has No Plans to Seek NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Finland's Prime Minister Paavo
Lipponen stressed here today that Finland has no plans to seek
membership of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"The starting point of our security policy solution is that
Finland is not a member of a military alliance but is responsible
for its own defense," Lipponen said in a speech at Germany's
Friedrich Ebert Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Lipponen, who is on a one-day visit to Bonn, met earlier with
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl. During the talks, he expressed
first of all his support for the bids for European Union (EU)
membership by the three Baltic states -- Estonia, Latvia and
Lithuania, a German government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
At the Friedrich Ebert Foundation, Lipponen stressed that the
three Baltic states had made impressive reform progress within the
past few years and should be treated as equal candidates for EU
membership.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Helsinki did not believe certain Eastern European
countries should be given a privileged position with regard to
joining the EU.
</P>
<P>
A stumbling block for Estonia and Latvia to join the EU is
their unresolved border disputes with Russia. The EU has said it
does not want to import any unresolved border problems with
admission of new members.
</P>
<P>
Lipponen said that while the border disputes remained primarily
bilateral issues, the EU could also play a role by encouraging a
solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
