<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Experts Want To Give Salvaged Warship Original Look </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The salvaged cruiser "Chungshan,"
which was sent to the bottom of the Yangtze River by Japanese
planes nearly 60 years ago, should be restored to its 1920s
appearance, some Chinese archaeologists, historians and shipping
people said today.
</P>
<P>
The warship, which was named for the forerunner of China's
democratic revolution, Dr. Sun Yat-sen (Sun Chungshan), should
keep its battle scars earned in the Battle of Jinmen in the War of
Resistance Against Japan and should remain floating as an
exhibition, the group of experts said after doing a feasibility
study of various restoration plans.
</P>
<P>
The ship was built by Japan in 1910, and took part in battles
in the 1920s against feudal warlords, under the command of Dr. Sun
Yat-sen.
</P>
<P>
Other restoration plans considered were for it to be restored
to its appearance when it sank in 1938, or that when it was hauled
out of the water on January 28.
</P>
<P>
But experts rejected the latter right away, in view of serious
damage done to the ship. "Keeping the vessel as it is now does
little for the ship's long-term protection, and makes it
impossible to carry it from the dockyard to the exhibition site,"
they explained.
</P>
<P>
The vessel was recovered after a 98-day salvage operation, and
is receiving an overhaul at a shipyard in central China's Hubei
province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
