<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Artist Arrested in Body Parts Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- A British artist has been arrested
for questioning after around 30 human body parts were found in his
studio, police said today.
</P>
<P>
Anthony-Noel Kelly, 41, was released on bail and will appear in
court next week, police said.
</P>
<P>
He is a cousin of the Duke of Norfolk and part-time teacher at
heir to the throne Prince Charles's Institute of Architecture.
</P>
<P>
He was detained last week after police raided his London studio
and country house with discovery of the human body parts.
</P>
<P>
Kelly refused to comment on the case but his lawyer, Mark
Stephens, said Kelly was cooperating with police.
</P>
<P>
"Police are investigating allegations of theft and burying
bodies without consent," a police spokeswoman told the press.
</P>
<P>
Police began the probe after the government's Inspector of
Anatomy, Laurence Martin, made a request for the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Martin is a civil servant in charge of anatomical
investigations, and was looking into possible violations of the
Anatomy Act, which forbids the illegal use of human body parts.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Department of Health said he had also
written to medical schools in Britain alerting them to the
possible sale of human remains.
</P>
<P>
Police said they were revolted by what they found during the
raids.
</P>
<P>
"There were some 20 to 30 pieces of human remains. It was
frankly unbelievable. Even for officers used to dealing with some
horrific case, it was sickening," a police officer told The Mirror
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Kelly won recognition for his moulds of heads, feet and torsos
which he claimed was his way of immortalizing the dead. Some of
his works, gilded in silver and gold, were sold for thousands of
pounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
