<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Agencies Call For End to Female Genital Mutilation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Three United Nations agencies today
called for international support for efforts aimed at eliminating
female genital mutilation, that is widely practised in
Africa and parts of the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO), the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) and the United Nations Population Fund
(UNFPA) appealed to the international community and world leaders
to achieve a short-term goal of a major decline in the practice in
10 years.
</P>
<P>
A WHO press release said that more than 130 million girls and
women around the world had been subjected to such mutilation and a
further two million were at risk each year.
</P>
<P>
Most of the girls and women live in 28 African countries, and
some in Asia and the Middle East. They are also found in Europe,
Australia, Canada and the United States among immigrant
communities, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The operation, sometimes called female circumcision, involves
usually very painful partial or total removal of external female
genital organs, or their mutilation.
</P>
<P>
It is carried out, sociologists say, largely to encourage the
woman to remain a virgin until marriage and so be more attractive
to a potential husband.
</P>
<P>
The age of girls and women mutilated differs from region to
region, but in general most girls undergo it between the age of
four to 12, WHO said.
</P>
<P>
Doctors said the practice often leads to death through
infection, or at least life-long health problems as well as
infertility and childbirth complications.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to end the practice, WHO Director-General Hiroshi
Nakajima, UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy and UNFPA
Executive Director Nafis Sadik unveiled their joint plan to bring
about a major decline in 10 years and completely eliminate this
practice within three generations.
</P>
<P>
They said that the elimination of this unsafe and unjustifiable
practice based on misconceptions and myths will not only improve
the health of millions of women and children but also make a major
contribution to the promotion of human rights and gender equity.
</P>
<P>
The three agencies said that governments, international
organizations, political, religious and non-governmental
organizations as well as funding agencies should make concerted
efforts to eliminate the harmful practice. Inter-agency teams will
be formed at country level supported by international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The teams will try to change public opinion in the countries
concerned through education and to raise awareness about the harm
of the practice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
