<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Manufacturing Output Grows 0.2 Pct in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Britain's manufacturing output rose
by a weaker-than-expected 0.2 percent in February, giving a 1.8
percent year-on-year rise, according to figures released today by
the Office for National Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, total industrial production, which includes
utilities output, was 0.6 percent lower in February than the month
before, the largest fall since June 1996, but 1.5 percent higher
on the year.
</P>
<P>
Economists had forecast the country's factory output and
industrial production in the month to increase by 0.3 percent and
0.2 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that, although manufacturing output grew slightly
in February, it has been lagging behind the booming service sector
for a long time, and this posed a dilemma for the new government
no matter which party wins the general election on May 1.
</P>
<P>
They said that if the new government raised interest rates to
kill inflationary pressures, it would on the one hand run the risk
of further strengthening the pound, which has rallied steadily over
the last eight months and is hitting exports, and on the other
hand it would further weaken the manufacturing sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
