<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Tourism Industry Boom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The global tourism industry has
generally performed well over the past six years and is forecast
to continue growing to the end of the decade.
</P>
<P>
According to Euromonitor, a leading international market
analyst, the number of tourists was up 27 percent over the 1991-96
period to reach 592 million while receipts grew by 49 percent to
404 billion U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Europe dominates the world in terms of both international
arrivals and departures. France recorded the world's highest
number of arrivals in 1996 with almost 62 million. Germany is the
biggest individual outbound market with 79 million departures. But
the highest growth in outbound tourism was found in Eastern
Europe, with both Bulgaria and the Czech Republic in particular
recording a dramatic increase in departures over the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
Growth destinations within the Americas, the second popular
tourism region in terms of arrivals, are South America and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
The fastest growing tourism regions are North and Southeast
Asia, Australia and the Middle East. However, South Africa was the
best performing individual market over the 1991-95 period.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists will grow at an annual rate of 4 to 5
percent in the next few years, Euromonitor forecasts. The biggest
growth regions will be Asia-Pacific, the Middle East and South
America.
</P>
<P>
Asia is expected to provide the greatest potential for outbound
tourism over 1996-2000 as disposable incomes increase in many
regions, although much of the movement will be inter-regional,
Euromonitor says.
</P>
<P>
The cutting of the working week in China from 48 hours to 40
hours and the return of Hong Kong to China will encourage growth
of outbound and domestic tourism in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
