<HEADLINE> Maintaining Existing Trade Concession Urged in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 9 (Xinhua) -- African, Caribbean and Pacific
countries should lobby both the European Union (EU) and the World
Trade Organisation (WTO) to maintain existing trade concessions,
Zimbabwean minister of agriculture Denis Norman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Opening a two-day workshop on post-Lome IV opportunities for
agriculture in the Southern African Development Community (SADC),
Norman said negotiations for current preferences to be retained
should be coupled with exploring ways to strengthen the bloc's
economies to face the new economic order.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the future of the Lome Convention rests with
our ability to identify our specific needs and to unite in the
negotiation of those needs," said Norman.
</P>
<P>
He underscored the importance of SADC's mutual cooperation
with the EU through the Lome Convention, particularly in the
agricultural sector, which the minister said was the engine for
economic growth for most of the SADC economies.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was jointly organised by the Friedrich Ebert
Stiftung and the Food Security Technical and Administrative Unit.
</P>
