<HEADLINE> EU Calls to Prepare for End of Lome Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Southern Africa Development
Community (SADC) should prepare itself now to work out a mechnism
which will succeed Lome IV Convention when it expires in the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
Head of the European delegation in Zimbabwe Michael Laidler
warned here today that there was very little time left for
negotiations on the successor to the convention, and talks had to
start in September 1998, 18 months before it expired.
</P>
<P>
He urged SADC member states to gear themselves to fully
consult stakeholders across the spectrum during the run-up to the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Laidler was addressing delegates at a two-day workshop on post
Lome IV opportunities for SADC agriculture in Harare. His topic
was "national dialogue on the future of ACP-EU relations post
Lome IV."
</P>
<P>
He said the EU had among other proposals suggested that the
status quo in terms of development aid be maintained when the
convention expires, while a global agreement supplemented by
bilateral agreements and the break up of Lome into regional
agreements were worked out.
</P>
<P>
The EU was also proposing a global agreement with the Least
Developed Countries (LDCS) and other types of agreements with
more developed countries like Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Laidler said since becoming members of the Lome Convention in
1980, SADC member countries' trade had grown rapidly.
</P>
<P>
He added while standards of living had markedly improved, many
ACP states remained very poor with 41 of the 70 ACP countries
among the LDCS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
