<HEADLINE> Landmine Ban Campaigners Meet in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Anti-landmine activists from
southern Africa are meeting in Harare to lobby African leaders
for a total ban on the production of landmines in a continent
with an estimated 50 million planted mines.
</P>
<P>
The Harare meeting follows a conference held in Maputo in
February to press African governments to ban production,
stockpiling, trade and use of anti-personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Zimbabwe campaign to ban landmines Lawyers
Moyo said, "our goal of a mine-free southern Africa is feasible,
and nearer every day."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has said a ban is in the pipeline while south Africa
and Mozambique have already announced a ban.
</P>
<P>
Malawi and Swaziland have gone as far as declaring their
support for the Ottawa Ban treaty to be signed in December this
year with more than 50 countries having already indicated their
readiness to sign the treaty.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 activists are attending the two-day meeting to
discuss ways of strengthening national campaigns with the aim of
making southern Africa mine-free. 
</P>
