<HEADLINE> Greek, Albanian Defense Ministers Meet in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos today discussed with Albanian Defense Minister
Shaqir Vukaj Athens' participation in the multinational security
force in Albania and in assisting the reconstruction of the
Albanian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The Greek defense minister said after the meeting that the
Greek corps would be made up of 700-900 troops, depending on
requirements and the final decision would be made Thursday in
cooperation with the Albanian government regarding the deployment
of the first troops on April 14.
</P>
<P>
Vukaj, who arrived here Tuesday, said that the future dangers
to be faced by the Italian-led multinational force were limited to
criminal gangs, as the Albanian people in both the north and south
of the country would welcome the multinational troops.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations approved recently the formation of a
5,000-strong peacekeeping force, half of which will be deployed
and half held in reserve, to protect the humanitarian relief
operations in the strife-ridden Albania.
</P>
<P>
Most Greek troops will be stationed in the Albanian capital of
Tirana, with another company based at the southern port of Vlore.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Greek minister revealed that during the meeting,
details of bilateral cooperation were worked out with regard to
Albania's reorganization of its armed forces, and discussions
would be continued at military level.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian minister stressed that the reconstruction would be
based on the history of the Albanian army, the traditions of the
people, the experience of the modern infrastructure of NATO member
states and that of other countries similar to Albania. 
</P>
