<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government for Peace Agreement With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar Al Bashir
has asserted here today that the government is willing to sign a
peace agreement with rebels to solve the problems in the south.
</P>
<P>
Addressing today's meeting of the Sudanese Supreme Peace
Council at the Friendship Hall, the Sudanese President said that
the government is to sign the final peace agreement with the
rebels immediately after Qurban Bairam (a festival for Muslims on
April 17).
</P>
<P>
The agreement has recently been initialed by the Sudanese
government and the rebel parties which have broken away from John
Garang, leader of the Popular Front for the Liberation of the
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The president said the signing of the peace agreement will constitute
a real beginning of a comprehensive solution of the Sudanese
problem, while stressing that bilateral negotiations, without any
external party, will be far more positive.
</P>
<P>
Bashir said the serious approach of the Sudanese government has
encouraged large numbers of southern Sudanese citizens, in and out
of the Sudan, to take part in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the importance of confidence-building between
rebel factions and the government as well as the provision of
sufficient guarantees.
</P>
<P>
The supreme peace council announced Sunday that the final
signing of the peace agreement would take place on April 10. It
also revealed the articles of the agreement including the
establishment of a coordination council, the appointment of 13
ministers and 10 governors for the southern Sudanese states,
specification of a four-year transition period culminating in a
public plebiscite, and distribution of power between the federal
government and governments of the various states. 
</P>
