<HEADLINE> Survey Indicates Bosnia, Beef Crisis Tarnish EU Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- A majority of the members of the
European parliament feel that the European Union's (EU) handling
of the Bosnia conflict and the "mad cow" crisis over British beef
tarnished its public image, according to a poll due to be
published today.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted by MORI for the London-based newspaper
European, revealed that the beef crisis inflicted the most serious
damage with 57 percent polled saying it had diminished public
perceptions of the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed a global ban on British beef exports last March
after the British government admitted possible links between mad
cow disease and its human equivalent Creutzfeldt Jacob Disease.
</P>
<P>
The non-cooperation policy adopted by the British government
effectively paralyzed the strongest economic bloc for some months.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that a narrow majority of 51 percent of
those surveyed felt that the EU's failure to resolve the Balkan
crisis highlighted its inability in handling major international
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
