<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Attacks SLA Militia in Southern Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 9 (Xinhua) - Guerrillas of the Lebanese
Hezbollah, or Party of God, launched a bombing attack on a patrol
of the South Lebanon Army (SLA) militia in the south this
afternoon, wounding three.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-strong surrogate militia of Israel confirmed that its
three militiamen were wounded in the attack in the so called
"security zone" set up by Israel in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah said that its fighters detonated a bomb targeting the
SLA patrol on a road between the towns of Gantara and Beni Hyan in
the north sector of the buffer zone at 2:30 p.m. local time (11:30
GMT).
</P>
<P>
Following the attack, the Israeli forces and the SLA militia
bombarded the vicinity of some south Lebanese villages near the
Israeli-occupied border strip without causing casualties, security
sources in the area reported.
</P>
<P>
This was the second bloody attack by Hezbollah guerrillas at
the SLA militia since this month. In the previous attack on April
1, one militiaman was killed and five others wounded.
</P>
<P>
Trades of fire between Muslim guerrillas on the one hand and
the Israeli forces and the SLA militia on the other constitute a
daily scene in the area.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone"
in 1985 in a bid to protect northern Israel from cross-border
attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
