<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German "Wise Men" Cast Doubt on Punctual Launching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Doubts that Germany will make the
grade for the single European currency, the euro, gained new force
today when two top German government economic advisers said they
expected a delay in the planned January 1, 1999 start date of the
euro.
</P>
<P>
"Given the persistent economic slack in Germany, the
fulfillment of the participation criteria (for the euro) is not in
sight," said Herbert Hax, head of the so-called "five wise men,"
a politically independent economic advisory panel for the German
government.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Koelnischen/Bonner Rundschau
newspaper, Hax also said that other EU states had the same
problems as Germany and a European Monetary Union (EMU) with only
a few participants "makes no sense."
</P>
<P>
The Maastricht treaty of the European Union has set five
criteria for member states to qualify for the euro. Among them are
that the budget deficit and national debt of a member country must
not exceed 3 and 60 percent respectively of its gross domestic
product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Also a flexible interpretation of these criteria was seen by
Hax as not helpful. "It is better to adhere to the strict
interpretation of the criteria, and if necessary, to postpone the
euro," he said.
</P>
<P>
Another member of the "five wise men," Rolf Peffekoven, today
also expressed doubt about EU members' ability to meet the 1999
start date of the euro with strict adherence to the qualifying
criteria.
</P>
<P>
"Because a watering down of the criteria is out of
consideration for the Bonn government, the euro would probably
come one or two years behind schedule," the Express newspaper
quoted Peffekoven as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Palestinian Confidence In Peace Is Waning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The level of trust in the
peace process has decreased ever since the construction of the
Jewish settlement by Israel in Mt. Abu Ghneim (Har Homa),
according to a latest poll conducted by JMCC, a Palestinian
press service based in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll released today, a comparison of the
results between an unpublished JMCC poll on March 7 and the
current one, shows a remarkable shift in the mood of the
Palestinian public opinion toward various aspects of the ailing
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Whereas in previous polls the levels of support, strong and
somewhat, for the peace process remained stable, the support
level declined from 78 percent to 73 percent in the period
between the latest two polls. Meanwhile, opposition, strong and
somewhat, to the peace process increased from 18.8 percent to
23.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the period, there was a clear drop in support for the
various Palestinian factions. Those, who said they do not trust
any political or religious factions increased from 21.3 percent
to 25.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
Trust in President Yasser Arafat decreased from 47.4 percent
to 43.4 percent and the number of Palestinians who said they do
not trust any Palestinian leader also increased from 15 percent
to 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
Although the majority of Palestinians oppose military and
suicide operations against Israeli targets, a large minority
believe that these operations are an adequate response to the
current political developments: 39.8 percent of the respondents
said they support military operations against Israeli targets
compared to 47.7 percent who oppose them. The difference between
support and opposition to military operations in the West Bank
is very low, 41.6 percent and 42.7 percent respectively. In
contrast, the figures in Gaza are 37 percent and 55.7 percent
respectively. Similar differences are also found between the West
Bank and Gaza in regard to suicide attacks, although the level of
opposition to suicide operations is higher in both the West Bank
and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
An increase in Palestinian frustration with the current
Israeli measures can be inferred from the level of support to
popular protests against Israel: 62.7 percent of Palestinians
support the intensification of demonstrations and popular
protests. Moreover, 31.3 percent of Palestinians believe that
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) should encourage these
protests, and 37.5 percent say that the PNA should not
interfere. Only 23.1 percent of the respondents say that the PNA
should prevent these popular protests.
</P>
<P>
The mojority of the Palestinians reject Israeli Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu's proposal to stop the
implementation of the interim agreement and to begin with the
final status negotiations; 67.6 percent of Palestinians believe
that the Palestinian leadership should not accept the proposal.
</P>
<P>
A random sample of 1,200 people over the age of 18 were
interviewed face-to-face throughout the West Bank and Gaza Strip
on April 3 and 4. The interviews were conducted in randomly
selected homes, and the subjects inside each home were also
selected randomly according to Kish tables. The interviews were
conducted in 60 sampling points chosen randomly according to
population.
</P>
<P>
The margin of error if 3 percent, with a confidence level of
95 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
