<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mkapa Appeals for International Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 9 (Xinhua) -- President Benjamin Mkapa
today met with 16 foreign envoys and representatives of U.N.
Agencies in Dar es Salaam, informing them on the food deficit
that is facing the country and what assistance is needed.
</P>
<P>
According to a press statement issued by the President's
Office, his briefing to the envoys was in line with his speech to
the nation on the food situation that he delivered through the
electronic media on Monday.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa informed them of the government's efforts so
far in the endeavor to send emergency food aid to those who
mostly need it immediately.
</P>
<P>
He said 10,000 tons have been allocated to the affected
regions from the Strategic Grain Reserve (SGR) which is being
transported on government expense close to the affected areas to
minimize the costs to the distributors.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa however said the available food stocks in SGR would be
insufficient to meet the food requirements to 3.6 million people,
670,800 of whom need free allocations.
</P>
<P>
He therefore called on the envoys to tell their governments
and agencies that Tanzania would need some 1.3 million U.S.
Dollars to replenish SGR stocks used as food aid.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Mkapa said the NGOs that have been appointed to
distribute the food aid to the affected localities would need
more funds to meet operational costs.
</P>
<P>
He also said some 1.2 million US Dollars would be required for
the purchase of seeds for farmers, especially for short-term
maize and sorghum seeds.
</P>
<P>
According to Mkapa, immediate food aid requires 14,000 tons to
add to the 10,000 tons already released from the SGR and the
11,000 pledged by the World Food Program.
</P>
<P>
Some 35,000 tons of food relief is immediately required to the
most adversely affected people by drought and the recent floods.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president said the government would need to be
assisted in paying for the distribution of food inside the
country at least to the regional and district centers before NGOs
take it over.
</P>
<P>
During the brief meeting at the State House here, a number of
envoys expressed readiness to assist.
</P>
<P>
The invited envoys were from Canada, The United Kingdom,
Italy, France, Spain, Belgium, Sweden, Ireland, Finland, South
Africa, Switzerland, China, South Korea, Egypt, resident
representatives of the UNDP and the World Food Program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
