<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Refutes the Netherlands' Unwarranted Accusations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Alternate Representative of the
Chinese delegation today refuted a Dutch representative's
unwarranted accusations against China in a statement Tuesday on
behalf of the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
"The Dutch turned a blind eye to the substantial progress made
by the Chinese government in the field of human rights, claiming
that `it is not sufficient' and making unwarranted accusations
against China of violating human rights," Li said in a reply to
the EU statement.
</P>
<P>
"These accusations are nothing more than cliches without
factual basis," he told the 53rd session of the United Nations
Commission on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
"Whether China has made sufficient progress or not in the field
of human rights should be judged by the Chinese people themselves
but not by the Western countries," Li said. "In the view of the
EU, only when China has accepted their political and value system,
will they say that `it is sufficient.' This is only a wishful
thinking."
</P>
<P>
Refuting the same Dutch's accusations against China on the
question of Hong Kong, Li stressed the following points:
</P>
<P>
1. An important component of the Chinese government's basic
policy on HK is to safeguard the human rights fo the residents in
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR). In accordance
with the Sino-British Joint Declaration and the Basic Law of the
HKSAR, the Chinese government, upon the resumption of its
sovereignty over HK, will implement the policy of "one country,
two systems," "rule of HK by HK people" and "a high degree of
autonomy for HK." This will provide a sound basis for the
promotion and protection of the human rights, democracy and
freedom of the HK people. Accordingly, the previous social and
economic system and way of life in HK shall remain unchanged for
fifty years; the laws previously in force in HK remain basically
unchanged. The Sino-British Joint Declaration and the Basic Law
have also fully and comprehensively guaranteed the rights and
freedom of the HK residents. They have also included clear-cut
stipulations on the development of a democratic political system
in HK.
</P>
<P>
2. It is none other than the HK British Authorities which have
created obstacles to the enjoyment of human rights, democracy and
freedom by the HK people. In running HK for more than a century,
the HK British Authorities have never drafted any Bill of Rights,
nor have they granted HK residents the right to elect public
officials. Yet on the very eve of HK's return to China, the HK
British Authorities hurriedly adopted the Hong Kong Bill of Rights
Ordinance and dished out its Proposals for Political Reforms. This
is a gross violation of the Sino-British Joint Declaration and the
principle of convergence with the Basic Law as well as the
relevant agreements and understanding reached between the Chinese
and British sides. Their purpose is to create chaos and obstacles
to the rule of law and the government administration in HK after
its return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
In order to ensure HK's smooth transition and handover of
government and preserve its long-term prosperity and stability,
the Chinese government cannot but take the necessary measures. The
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress has come to a
decision on the handling of the question of HK's existing laws.
With respect to the HK Bill of Rights Ordinance, it was decided
that only those articles which were given overriding effect would
not be adopted, while the rest of the ordinance will be applicable
upon the return of HK to China. The manner in which the Chinese
side has dealt with the legal issue is fair and reasonable, and
has won the wide support of the HK community.
</P>
<P>
"The return of HK to China will have positive and long-standing
effects on world peace and development," Li noted. "Certainly,
there will always be some people who are still nostalgic about
colonialism and could not help but resort to vicious calumny and
make troubles for the Chinese government. They may even attempt to
internationalize the question of HK in order to disrupt its
prosperity and stability. But their attempts will only turn out to
be futile." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
