<HEADLINE> Zairian Rebel Radio Announces Capture of Lubumbashi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Zairian rebel radio announced
this evening the capture of the country's "economic lung" and
second largest city Lubumbashi, which is also the capital of the
fabulously mineral rich province of Shaba in the southeast of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) said that the inhabitants of
Lubumbashi welcomed the rebel soldiers "with cries of joy," as the
latter entered the city after a fierce battle with the elite
Special Presidential Division (DSP), the presidential guard of
President Mobutu Sese Seko, over the control of a residence of
Mobutu which was used as the headquarters of the DSP.
</P>
<P>
AFP said that with the capture of Lubumbashi, the rebels of
Laurent-Desire Kabila have made a big step forward in its conquest
of all the territory of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The rebel radio, "Voice of the People," said that the rebel
soldiers took control of the city by 14:00 (1200 GMT) "despite the
apparent resistance of the DSP supported by Belgian mercenaries."
</P>
<P>
"As things are going with such a speed, we wonder why the FAZ
(Zairian Armed Forces) continues to fight. What is the FAZ waiting
for -- for surrendering?" said the radio.
</P>
<P>
It said that the objective of the rebels, which is to "liberate
all the country," "is on the way to be won."
</P>
<P>
AFP said that it is impossible now to estimate the number of
people killed in the fighting for Lubumbashi today, although some
rebel soldiers said that the DSP inflicted heavy losses on the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
Few civilians were killed in the fighting, and a Belgian
expatriate was seriously wounded in mortar shellings and has been
sent to Kinshasa by plane by his friends, said AFP.
</P>
<P>
About 550 Belgian soldiers are preparing to evacuate to
neighboring Zambia or the Congo the hundreds of Belgians living in
Shaba province, where Zaire's state mineral company Gecamine is
located.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted unconfirmed reports as saying that the DSP had blown
up installations of Gecamine before fleeing Mount Simba, 15
kilometers southwest of Lubumbashi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
