<HEADLINE> Public Hearing on TWA 800 Planned for Late Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government will
conduct a public hearing in late summer on the TWA Flight 800
tragedy last July that killed 230 people, National Transportation
Safety Board Chairman Jim Hall told a Senate committee today.
</P>
<P>
The TWA explosion has been the most investigated event of 1996,
Hall told the Senate Transportation Committee. It has kept
investigators on the scene for nine months so far, compared with
the one to three weeks in most airline accidents.
</P>
<P>
Mechanical failure, a bomb or a missile all remain under
investigation as possible causes of the crash.
</P>
<P>
Hall and officials of the Federal Aviation Administration and
the FBI were questioned by the committee about efforts to prevent
crashes and ensure aviation safety.
</P>
<P>
Hall told the committee that while it is apparent that an
explosion occurred in the center fuel tank of the Boeing 747, "the
origin of the explosion is not yet known."
</P>
<P>
"To date, with over 90 percent of the airplane recovered, there
is no physical evidence of a bomb or missile strike," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Dale Watson of the FBI's National Security Division said
his agency was still investigating the possibility of a criminal
act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
