<HEADLINE> Northern Irish Man Wounded in Shooting Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- A man from the Catholic Irish
sector was seriously wounded in a shooting attack near Belfast,
Northern Ireland, early this morning, according to British
security sources.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman was quoted by the BBC television as saying
this afternoon, "We are certainly treating it as attempted
murder."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that 23-year-old Kieran Delaney was
approached by a man disguised as a postman "who produced a pistol
from his postbag and fired a single bullet, striking the victim on
the neck."
</P>
<P>
"This morning's shooting bears all hallmarks of a sectarian
attack. I would urge people to remain calm and vigilant in the
days ahead," he said.
</P>
<P>
No one has so far claimed responsibility for the attack that
happened on a road that runs between a pro-British Protestant area
and a Catholic Irish zone in Belfast, he added.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland has suffered an upsurge of hostilities over
recent months by rival guerrilla groups as the all-party talks on
the future of Northern Ireland have run into a deadlock in the
run-up to the British general election.
</P>
<P>
The Irish Republican Army, fighting to end British rule in
Northern Ireland, has killed two British soldiers and masterminded
a series of bomb alerts, which caused massive disruptions.
</P>
<P>
Protestant "Loyalist" groups, who are determined to maintain
British rule, have also been blamed for killing two Catholics
since last July. 
</P>
