<HEADLINE> 350 French Soldiers to Leave for Albania Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The second group of 350 French
soldiers will leave the French port Toulon for Albania Thursday or
Friday on a peacekeeping mission aimed at securing humanitarian
aid to the Balkan state, said French military sources today.
</P>
<P>
The first group of 120 French soldiers left Toulon for the
Albanian port Durres Monday night.
</P>
<P>
France will send a total of 850 to 1,000 soldiers to Albania as
part of the six-nation multinational protection force in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Italian parliament today voted with an
overwhelming majority to authorize the country to command the
multinational force, which was proposed by the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe and approved by the United
Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
French troops will be stationed along the 40 kilometer long
road between Durres and Tirana and in the port installations of
Durres to protect the sending of humanitarian cargos to Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The remaining units of the French troops will arrive in Albania
before April 16.
</P>
<P>
The multinational force will be authorized to use force for
legitimate self-defense and to ensure the free circulation for
convoys carrying humanitarian materials.
</P>
<P>
The French troops will be accompanied with armored vehicles,
tanks, military helicopters, transport trucks and armored jeeps.
</P>
<P>
Apart from France and Italy, Turkey, Greece, Spain and Denmark
will also send troops to Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
