<HEADLINE> Iraqi Aircraft Returns Home After Sending Pilgrims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 9 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi airliner returned here
this evening after transporting Iraqi pilgrims to Saudi Arabia to
perform hajj, according to the Iraqi news agency.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft with 104 pilgrims on board, which belongs to the
Iraqi Airways, landed at the airport of Jeddah, a western city of
Saudi Arabia, at noon today, breaking a U.N. ban on international
flights from and out of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Two Saudi Arabian warplanes intercepted and escorted the Iraqi
aircraft to Jeddah and allowed the passengers to complete
necessary entry formalities for performing hajj.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Minister of Endowments and Religious Affairs
Abdul-Monim Ahmed Saleh told reporters at the Baghdad Airport that
the flight was aimed at transporting aged and ailing Iraqis who
would not be able to make the journey by land to Mecca.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, this flight has been the very first one by Iraqi
Airlines since the air ban was imposed on Iraq in 1990 following
its invasion of Kuwait. 
