<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Credits for Asian Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank announced here
today the approval of credits for a number of Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
A credit of 48 million U.S. dollars equivalent is provided for
the Third Highway Improvement Project in Laos. The project will
finance labor, equipment and consultant services to upgrade road
surfaces, and will provide road maintenance and technical
assistance to the Ministry of Communication, Transport, Post and
Construction for implementing the project.
</P>
<P>
Two credits totaling 35 million dollars equivalent are
earmarked for projects in the West Bank and Gaza, of which 25
million dollars will be for the West Bank and Gaza housing
project. It will finance a four-year program of policy and
institution building activities. Another 10 million dollar credit
is offered to finance an investment guarantee fund which will
lessen political risks for investors. Additional financing for the
fund will come from other sponsors.
</P>
<P>
A credit of some 1.4 million dollars equivalent will be used
for the Oil Institution Building in Georgia. The project will
finance a feasibility study of a major oil export pipeline from
Baku, Azerbaijan, to Supsa, Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Later last week, the World Bank also okayed a 10 million dollar
credit for Kazakstan's real estate registration pilot project. The
project will help finance a real estate registration pilot program
that will design and test models for establishing a unified real
estate registration system. The project will help enhance the
development of land and real estate markets in Kazakstan.
</P>
<P>
The credits will be channeled through the International
Development Association, the concessionary lending arm of the
World Bank for developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
