<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Launches Program to Promote Road Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) today
adopted a program to reduce the risk of road accidents, which have
become one of the main causes of death in EU countries.
</P>
<P>
The program, adopted on the initiative of Neil Kinnock, the EU
commissioner for transport, is aimed at addressing the issue of
road accidents between now and the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Some of the measures recommended by the European Commission,
the EU's executive body, are giving drivers correct information on
the safety provided by their vehicles, developing computer tools
to manage traffic better and reducing the risk of accidents due to
consumption of alcohol, drugs or medicines.
</P>
<P>
Some 45,000 people in the EU are killed each year on the roads,
said Kinnock, adding that the "dramatic human and social
consequences of this scourge" are compounded by a heavy economic
burden for society, estimated at around 1 million ECUs (about 1.3
million U.S. dollars) for each person killed.
</P>
<P>
The commission asked the EU member states and other related
decision makers to take a "systematic" look at the cost when
deciding whether or not to invest in or take regulatory measures
in favor of road safety. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
