<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Investment, Decisive for Environment: UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The private sector is now a
decisive factor in environmental protection and its scale will
increase rapidly in coming years, according to a paper released at
a United Nations Development Program press briefing today.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 300-600 billion dollars will be spent
globally by the year 2000 on pollution-control goods and services,
rivaling investment in the pharmaceutical industry, said the
paper, prepared by Bradford S. Gentry, director of the research on
private finance and the environment at the Yale Center for
Environmental Law and Policy.
</P>
<P>
A substantial part of the 1 trillion dollars needed for new
power-generation capacity in developing countries and economies in
transition between 1993 and 2000 will be directed to renewable
energy projects. An additional 250 billion is expected to be
absorbed by energy efficiency projects over the next 20 years, the
paper noted.
</P>
<P>
Although the bulk of environmental investment remains within
the industrialized countries, it is in the developing countries
and the economies in transition that the highest up-side potential
exists, the paper read.
</P>
<P>
The paper suggested that a framework for encouraging
environmental investment be established in these countries.
</P>
<P>
Given the scale of their environmental needs and the distinct
improbability of any substantial increase in public-sector aid
flows, governments in developing and transition countries are
looking to private capital as the primary instrument for financing
environmentally sustainable development, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Overall flows of private capital to developing and transition
countries between 1989 and 1994 quadrupled, reaching a level three
times greater than official development assistance, the paper
noted.
</P>
<P>
The paper also showed that the environmental sound projects are
commercially attractive. "These studies demonstrate the simple
equation: investment plus environment equals profit," said James
Gustave Speth, administrator of the UNDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany to Decide Fate of UNIDO Membership in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Germany plans to decide whether to
stay in or quit the United Nations Industrial Development
Organization (UNIDO) during the course of this year, the German
Ministry of Foreign Economic Cooperation and Development said
today.
</P>
<P>
The remark was made by the ministry's state secretary Wighard
Haerdtl during talks with visiting UNIDO general director Mauricio
de Maria y Campos.
</P>
<P>
Campos meanwhile warned that the existence of the UNIDO would
be threatened if Germany did withdraw.
</P>
<P>
With an annual contribution of 17 million German marks, or
about 10 million U.S. dollars, Germany is currently the second
largest contributor to the UNIDO after Japan.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Canada have both left the UNIDO. Britain
and Australia have said they will follow suit at the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Accusing the UNIDO of failing to carry out needed reforms,
German Development Minister Carl-Dieter Spranger last year also
urged Bonn to quit the organization. But that call met opposition
from Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, thus delaying a final
decision.
</P>
<P>
Set up in 1967, the Vienna-based UNIDO has a mandate to foster
industrial development in developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
