contributing to economic development in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at his home at Butiama, Mara Region in
northwestern Tanzania, the former president said the institutions
stand a chance to promoting the economy if they are given a fair
ground to operate on.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, who granted an interview to reporters as part of the
festivities to commemorate his 75th birthday next Sunday, said
some institutions and parastatals had failed because most of them
were directed to implement some projects which were unprofitable.
</P>
<P>
He lauded the free market economic policy in the country,
saying it is bound to strengthen the economy but cautioned that
the system should not be wrongly implemented to create rifts in
the society.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, who stepped down from presidency in 1985, was
committed to a centralized economy during his tenure in office.
</P>
<P>
His successor, Ali Hassan Mwinyi and present President
Benjamin Mkapa, embarked on a liberalized economy, encouraging
private enterprises and privatization of ailing public
corporations which are a burden to the country's economy.
