<HEADLINE> S. African Police Confiscate Crayfish After Red </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 9 (Xinhua) -- About five tons of rock
lobsters taken from the beach at Elands Bay in Western Cape
Province have been confiscated by the police who set up road
blocks in the area, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 tons of crayfish "walked out" of the sea onto
the Cape West Coast beaches at the weekend to escape the toxic
red tide which depletes oxygen levels in the waters.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people descended on the beaches to collect the
crayfish, using refuse bags, empty milk carton containers and
laundry baskets, despite not having permits to do so.
</P>
<P>
They seemed oblivious to the fact that only four crayfish per
person may be taken from the sea.
</P>
<P>
The crayfish confiscated in the road blocks would be taken to
fish factories under the control of the Sea Fisheries
Directorate, but those alive would be relocated to the ocean,
said the source.
</P>
<P>
The weekend walk-out was the second time in the past two weeks
that huge numbers of crayfish crawled in from the sea. About 60
tons of crayfish crawled onto the beaches in the areas shortly
before Easter.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cape Attorney-General Frank Kahn warned on Tuesday
that people collecting crayfish without a permit or those caught
in possession of more than four crayfish would be prosecuted,
irrespective of whether the crayfish were dead or alive.
</P>
<P>
However, the Environmental Affairs and Tourism Ministry said
earlier that it would consider allowing people without permits to
collect the delicacy which had washed up on the beach.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the current legislation prohibited people
without permits from catching crayfish from the ocean, not from
collecting washed-up crayfish.
</P>
<P>
Residents in the region have reportedly requested permission
to sell the crayfish, said the source.
</P>
<P>
A police source said they just confiscated the crayfish, but
did not arrest those who were caught in the road blocks. But a
number of people selling the crayfish in surrounding towns had
been arrested and would be prosecuted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
