<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: What Will Strong Pound Bring About to UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Britain's economy is continuing to
grow at a steady pace, with 0.8% expansion in the first quarter of
this year, leaving GDP 2.6 % higher than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
But the contradiction between consumers and industry remains
wide and could widen further this year under the influence of the
strong pound.
</P>
<P>
The pound gained almost 4 pfennigs against the German deutsche
mark early this week. It closed at D-mark 2.7884 in London market
on Monday, above its old European exchange rate mechanism(ERM)
floor of D-mark 2.7780, a rise of 3.94 pfennigs on the day.
</P>
<P>
That is pound's highest level since its membership of the ERM
was suspended on September 16, 1992, when Britain was unable to
defend the pound against currency speculation in foreign currency
exchange markets.
</P>
<P>
Since pound's rapid rise began in August last year, it has
gained more than 15 % against the currencies of its main trading
partners.
</P>
<P>
While the appreciation of pound will have an adverse impact on
economic activity this year, the beneficial effects on inflation
are already clear.
</P>
<P>
Raw material costs from abroad are dropping sharply, while core
factory gate inflation is at a thirty-year low, according to the
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Economists here believe that these favorable development will
allow goods inflation to fall sharply, even if stronger consumer
activity enables retailers to widen margins aggressively.
</P>
<P>
They expect that this should easily outweigh any further rise
in services inflation and allow underlying inflation to fall to
2.25% by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
However, a worsening trade deficit with non-European countries
in the first two months provided the warning sign that pound's
strength might start to have a negative impact on trade.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures by the Office for National
Statistics, the non-EU deficit rose to 554 million pounds (886
million US dollars) in February from 339 million pounds (542
million US dollars) in January.
</P>
<P>
One among the hardest hit is Britain's manufacturing export. It
is now at the lowest level since 1993.
</P>
<P>
In its latest monthly trends survey, the Confederation of
British Industry (CBI) says that pound's continued strength has
led to export demand for UK manufactured goods reaching its lowest
level since November 1993.
</P>
<P>
The survey of more than 1,000 firms in 50 industries, consider
their export books below normal. Only 17% say their export books
are above normal.
</P>
<P>
The growing impact of the strong pound on Britain's export was
also highlighted by the poor performance of the engineering
sector.
</P>
<P>
Graham Mackenzie, chairman of the Engineering Employer's
Federation (EEF), recently said: "The strength of the pound has
caused a marked deterioration over the last quarter."
</P>
<P>
"We believe the pound-dollar relationship is about right at the
moment, but there is cause for concern in sterling's value against
the deutsche mark," he added.
</P>
<P>
Brian Clayton, chairman of the UK Steel Association agrees: "We
are less competitive with the mark at current levels."
</P>
<P>
He said: "In the steel industry we are concerned that if
interest rates go up after an election, the pound will strengthen
still further and the situation will get worse."
</P>
<P>
It is understood that over 70% of the sales revenue of
Britain's steel industry is linked to the deutsche mark.
</P>
<P>
The negative impact on Britain's economic activities of the
continuing strength of the pound reflects the hardening
consensus that exchange rates will need to rise steeply after the
election, no matter who wins the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
