<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Tells Member States to Reduce Tariffs by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Council of Ministers of the
Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) today
urged its members to immediately reduce their tariffs by 80
percent in accordance with the agreed time-table.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Ministers said in a report adopted here that
all member countries except Lesotho, Swaziland and Namibia should
have reduced their tariffs by 80 percent by October last year.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho and Swaziland have been exempted because they have a
derogation until September this year while Namibia has until
January next year to publish the COMESA tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Burundi has also requested to be exempted from publishing
COMESA tariffs for five years on the ground that war and economic
sanctions imposed against it have seriously affected its economy.
</P>
<P>
So far Comoros, Sudan, Uganda and Zimbabwe have reduced their
tariffs by 80 percent while Kenya, Malawi and Mauritius are
currently going to realize the 80 percent reduction.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the member countries have reduced their tariffs by
60 to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA aims to eliminate non-tariff barriers and achieve
zero tariff in COMESA by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
