<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental Settlements Bank is Needed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- An International Bank for
Environmental Settlements, a new global institution for pollution
control and sustainable development, will help redress
environmental imbalances of the past 50 years, according to a
paper released at a UNDP press briefing today.
</P>
<P>
The aim is to develop innovative financial institutions and
instruments to obtain market value from environmental resources
without destroying them, reads the paper prepared by Graciela
Chichilnisky, Chairperson of Mathematics and Economics of UNESCO
and Director of Program on Information and Resources at Columbia
University.
</P>
<P>
The paper notes that a system of national accounts introduced
since World War II has supported the activities of the World Bank,
the International Monetary Fund and the GATT, which have led the
world economy into an unprecedented period of industrialization,
material expansion and global commerce.
</P>
<P>
But as the century turns, industrial society's voracious use of
the earth's resources has reached its logical limits and the
massive infrastructure that supports the survival of human species
is under threat, the paper warns.
</P>
<P>
The new global financial institution is designed to be
sensitive where the World Bank, the IMF and WTO fall short, the
paper notes.
</P>
<P>
The International Bank of Environmental Settlements proposed in
the paper is fundamentally different from a standard financial
market and will have a much larger role than a stock market.
</P>
<P>
The principles discussed in the paper will apply to the use of
all environmental assets, such as biodiversity, soil and forests.
</P>
<P>
Emissions trading, the global reinsurance of environmental
risks, and the securitization of the earth's biodiversity
resources are natural financial instruments that merge the
interest of private financial markets with international
development policy, according to the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
