<HEADLINE> Thatcher Boosts Conservatives by Attacking Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Former British prime minister
Margaret Thatcher today openly attacked opposition Labor leader
Tony Blair for trying to take over her policies.
</P>
<P>
To boost Prime Minister John Major's election campaign,
Thatcher for the first time appeared on the road in the campaign
for a May 1 election.
</P>
<P>
When asked if people were wrong to believe that Blair rather
than Conservative Prime Minister John Major was her ideological
heir apparent, Thatcher gave a negative answer.
</P>
<P>
"They have got the sex wrong. I think they have got the
willpower wrong. I think they have got the reasoning wrong. I
think they have got the strength wrong," Thatcher told reporters
on the stump at a football ground in Aldershot southwest of
London.
</P>
<P>
Thatcher, Britain's famous "Iron Lady", stepped down in 1990
after 11 years in Downing Street to be succeeded by Major. She has
become Britain's longest-serving prime minister of this century
and had high reputation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that local media has often suggested Thatcher
admires Blair's leadership style, the former prime minister said
Blair would hand back powers to the trade unions and to
bureaucrats of the European Union if he were to win.
</P>
<P>
"He is trying to take over my policies in part. It's a kind of
conversion of convenience. I had to make the revolution happen by
changing everything I found in Britain," she added.
</P>
<P>
The Conservative Party is lagging behind the Labor by more than
20 percentage points in national opinion polls, and Major is
tipped to lose the election.
</P>
<P>
Thatcher's intervention to support Major in the campaign was
immediately welcomed by the Conservatives which definitly needs
her support.
</P>
<P>
"She is an incredibly good campaigner. She was a superb prime
minister and she's doing her bit, which is incredibly valuable," a
Conservative spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
In the past, Thatcher has often damned Major with faint praise
although he was her hand-picked successor.
</P>
<P>
But an aide of Thatcher said she planned about nine trips on
the trail this month to show her full support for the Conservative
party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
