<HEADLINE> Canada's Liberal Maintains Lead in Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Liberal Party still
enjoys a strong popularity as the clock ticks down to an election
call, a new poll has found.
</P>
<P>
On a national basis, the ruling Liberal Party has the support
of 47 percent of decided voters, according to a new
Globe-Environics poll.
</P>
<P>
The Liberals are followed by the Progressive Conservative Party
at 16 percent; the New Democratic Party (NDP), the Bloc Quebecois
and the Reform Party at 12 percent each; and others at 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The support levels reflect a recalculation of results after the
removal of the 27 percent who said they were undecided, the Globe
and Mail newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Liberal Party appears likely to be re-elected with a
majority, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
According to computer-assisted predictions prepared for the
paper, the Liberals could take a high of 222 seats to a low of 178
in the 301-seat House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the Bloc Quebecois would get 50 to 62 seats,
the Reform five to 50, the Progressive Conservative seven to 14
and the NDP nine or 10.
</P>
<P>
The poll of 1,961 eligible voters, conducted between March 11
and 31, has a margin error of plus or minus 2.2 percentage points,
19 times out of 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
