<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
said here today that the government will continue its all-out war
against crimes, particularly kidnapping as he called on local
executives and law enforcers to join hands in the anti-crime
drive.
</P>
<P>
The mechanisms in fighting crimes are there, including the
criminal justice system which has been reinforced by recognizing
and involving various citizen groups, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that the government will also press its drive
against scalawags in the military and the police forces, adding a
special task force set up one and a half years ago had expelled at
least 1,300 scalawags in uniform.
</P>
<P>
"This (scalawags-removing campaign) has also been enlarged by
the Department of Justice to other law enforcement agencies,"
Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
The president said he constantly called upon the law enforcers
to perform their responsibilities as far as the effect on
investments, trade and tourism development as well as the economic
momentum in the country are concerned.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that 241 people were kidnapped in the country
last year with millions of pesos paid as ransom. For the first
quarter of this year, at least 50 kidnapping cases occurred.
</P>
<P>
Kidnap victims charged that some policemen and government
soldiers are kidnappers or protectors of kidnappers.  
