<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Capital Looking for New Overseas Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- A breakthrough is needed to put
more overseas funds into cash-strapped state-owned enterprises, Yi
Xiqun, director of the Beijing Municipal Foreign Economic
Relations and Trade Commission, said today.
</P>
<P>
In addition to overseas listings, introducing international
investment fund into China's stock market is another way worth
considering, he told an international symposium on overseas
fund-raising today.
</P>
<P>
"As a center of China's financial institutions and home to more
than 200 foreign representative offices and 11 overseas bank
branches, Beijing will prove to be an ideal site for overseas
investors," Yi noted.
</P>
<P>
The capital city had approved 12,789 overseas-funded ventures
by the end of March, involving 10.6 billion US dollars in foreign
capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
