<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Manufacturing Production Down in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's output of
manufactured products declined by 5.5 percent in February this
year, compared to a year ago as the majority of industries
produced less, the Economic Development Board (EDB) said today.
</P>
<P>
As a result, cumulative output of the first two months of 1997
was 6.3 percent below what was achieved in the same period of
1996, it said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that some major segments of the key electronics
industry remained depressed, with overall output falling by 7.8
percent as the output from the semiconductors and consumer
electronics segments decreased.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that output of disk drives and
telecommunication equipment continued to grow, cumulative output
of the electronics industry for the first two months of this year
was 9.6 percent lower than that in the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in the electronics industry affected the output in
the fabricated metal products and plastic products industries, the
EDB said. Declines of 8.3 percent and 12.2 percent were recorded
respectively in the two industries and the total output for the
first two months shrank by 7.4 percent and 18.2 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The output of petroleum products fell by 11.9 percent as
refiners were hit by poor margins caused by slackened demand after
winter. Cumulative output for the first two months was reduced by
7.2 percent compared to a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The transport equipment industry declined by 11.2 percent as
output from the marine segment remained depressed with shipyards
engaged in small value repair jobs, while the output of machinery
dropped by 12.4 percent with a decrease in the output of
refrigerating equipment, dies and moulds and specialized
machinery, the EDB said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
