<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Defense Minister Threatens to Reoccupy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai today said Israel will have no problem in
reoccupying Hebron and other Palestinian cities in the West Bank,
reported the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai made the remarks when he was speaking to reporters.
But he added that this is not desirable.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that Israel wants to know whether the
Palestinians would stand by the agreements they signed. Under
the agreements, he noted, there is security cooperation in the
field.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai is the second government minister who has made
belligerent statements against the Palestinians in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Tzahi Hanegbi warned that should the
September bloody incident reoccur, that would mean an all-round
war between Israel and Palestine and (Palestinian leader Yasser)
Arafat will have to go in exile again.
</P>
<P>
Israel opened a tunnel last September near the holy site of the
Al Aqsa Mosque of the Old City in Jerusalem, which resulted in
great anger from the Palestinians and the later
Israeli-Palestinian violence killing seven people and wounding
more than 300 others.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Dahlan, head of the Palestinian Preventive Security
Service in Gaza, reacted cooly to Mordechai's threats, saying
that the Israeli minister's statement is unnecessary and it only
added tension between the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Dahlan said that the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) and police
could easily enter Palestinian cities, but there was no
guarantee that they could easily get out.
</P>
<P>
Dahlan declared that the security coordination between the
two sides will not resume until all agreements are implemented
in spite of the meeting between chief of Israel General Security
Service Ami Ayalon, U.S. Central Intelligence Agency officials
and Arafat in Gaza Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Palestinians will wait for the outcome of the
meetings between senior Palestinian and U.S. officials in
Washington in order to determine future security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Abu Mazen, member of the Executive Committee of the PLO, and
Saeb Erekat, Palestinian chief negotiator, flew to Washington
Wednesday night for talks with U.S. officials following the
summit meeting between President Bill Clinton and Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu there.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has reportedly expressed willingness to meet with
Palestinian representatives. Abu Mazen and Saeb Erekat will be
joined by Hanan Ashrawi, Palestinian minister of Higher
Education and former spokeswoman for the Palestinian peace
delegation who arrived in Washington last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
