<HEADLINE> HK Holidays Bill To Be Introduced to PLC Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive's Office of
 the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) today
published the Holidays (1997 and 1998) Bill, which provides for
additional holidays this year and general holidays in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The draft bill will be tabled to the Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) Saturday at the interim body's fourth plenary
meeting, according to a press release from the office.
</P>
<P>
The bill designates the first and second days of July and
October 1, 1997 as holidays with pay, in addition to the 11
statutory holidays already provided for under the Employment
Ordinance. The arrangement is valid for 1997 only.
</P>
<P>
In the case of general holidays, three additional days are
provided for in 1997. July 1 and 2, October 1 and 2, and a holiday
 in August to coincide with the victory of the anti-Japanese war
will be made public holidays, while the two holidays in August
provided for under the existing ordinance will be suspended.
</P>
<P>
For 1998, the total number of general holidays, apart from
Sundays, will remain at 17 days.
</P>
<P>
The draft bill followed relevant decision and suggestions
adopted last year by the HKSAR Preparatory Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
