<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Excavator Causes Gas Pipe Blast in Seoul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 10 (Xinhua) -- An excavator working on subway
construction in western Seoul this afternoon accidentally hit a
gas pipeline which caused a big explosion, much panic and snarled
traffic for hours -- but caused no casualties
</P>
<P>
Seoul police said the excavator, working on a sewer pipe in
Mapo district, accidentally scraped a gas pipeline. It caused a
spark which ignited leaking gas leading to the blast at a business
intersection.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said they heard a loud explosion at 1:46 p.m. (local
time) and saw a flame skyrocketing more than 30 meters.
</P>
<P>
Pedestrians and cars fled in panic, some people hurting their
legs and feet in the chaos.
</P>
<P>
Firemen took more than 20 minutes to control the fire, which
burned out the excavator along with communication lines and
underground facilities.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred just 400 meters from the site of another
gas pipeline explosion in December 1994, which killed 13 and
injured 66.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has seen a number of serious accidents in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
In April 1995, a gas blast at a subway construction site in the
southwestern city of Taegu killed 100 people, most of them
teenagers on their way to school. That explosion was caused by a
welding torch, according to police.
</P>
<P>
The public has called for more effective disaster-preventing
measures by the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Mayor Says Shanghai, Hong Kong Economies Complementary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Zhao Qizheng, the Vice-mayor of
Shanghai told delegates to the 32nd World Congress of the
International Chamber of Commerce here today that "the two
economies are complementary, not replaceable."
</P>
<P>
"Even though Shanghai intends to turn itself into a financial
center, the functions of the two cities are different," he said,
explaining that Shanghai is more like a retailer while Hong Kong
functions more like a wholesaler.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-five of the world's leading banks have branches in Hong
Kong, while only 47 overseas banks now have branches in Shanghai,
according to Zhao. Geographically, the two cities are "two road
lamps along the Asian economic corridor," and "with a distance of
1,500 kilometers, have different target regions and inland areas
to woo."
</P>
<P>
Zhao said that Shanghai, which is China's major industrial
processing base, can take full advantage of Hong Kong's status as
a free trade port. The two cities already have good economic
relations, he said, and trade between the two last year topped 3.5
billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Chinese Banker Calls for More Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- China will further open its
financial market and increase reforms to use more domestic and
overseas funds to support its economy, Wang Xuebing, president of
the Bank of China, told the 32nd World Congress of the
International Chamber of Commerce today.
</P>
<P>
China will work hard to make the renminbi fully convertible by
gradually loosening controls on buying and selling of foreign
exchange in the capital account and opening up its capital market
in a planned way.
</P>
<P>
State commercial banks will also be encouraged to expand
overseas business, as the nation's management of the foreign
exchange market improves and a capital market grows, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
"Direct fund-raising, or pooling of funds in the capital
market, has massive potential in China, given the fact that market
capitalization of stocks and bonds accounts for only 12 percent
and 11 percent respectively of the nation's GDP," he said.
</P>
<P>
China has great fund potential with a high saving rate, which
have stayed at around 35 percent since the nation adopted its
reform and opening-up policy in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the rate has already exceeded 40 percent and the
nation's total savings reached 826.5 billion US dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
"Overseas investment of various kinds will continue to be an
indispensable choice for healthy and rapid growth in China's
economy," Wang noted, citing listing of state-owned enterprises
overseas as an important means of raising foreign capital, while
China is issuing more bonds overseas.
</P>
<P>
There are 26 Chinese state enterprises listed overseas, that
have raised nearly five billion US dollars in foreign capital. By
issuing overseas bonds, China got 4.89 billion US dollars last
year alone, with the total amount since 1991 hitting 27.26 billion
US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
