<HEADLINE> Egypt Expects Balanced European Role in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Egypt expects Europe to chip in
balanced mediation efforts in dispersing the current crisis in the
Mideast peace process, Egyptian MENA news agency today quoted
Egptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa as saying.
</P>
<P>
European officials are considering a joint initiative with the
United States to push forward the peace process, said Moussa, who
is currently on a short visit to Kuwait after attending the
Non-Aligned Movement foreign ministers' meeting in New
Delhi, India.
</P>
<P>
"The European initiative is expected to be equilibrium," he
said.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came three days after tough White House talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu had achieved no
immediate breakthrough in restarting stalled Mideast peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. role is important and we are still expecting the
American move," he added.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the situation in the region, Moussa said that he does
not see anything optimistic as regards the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I am not optimistic about this issue but there is still some
hope and there is a chance for rescuing the situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the international community to take "a clear and
correct move" which would lead to salvaging the peace process.
</P>
<P>
There was little sign of progress on the diplomatic front to
revive peace moves that came to a halt last month over Netanyahu's
green light for bulldozers to begin work on a Jewish settlement on
the edge of Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu has asked the Europeans not to harbor any
unrealistic illusions about their role in the Mideast peace
process on the eve of his visit to the Netherlands, current
European Union (EU) rotating president.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's visit came at a time when EU officials stepped up
pressure for a greater role of the 15-nation bloc in the Mideast
peace-making.
</P>
<P>
They said the escalating violence in the region would be on the
agenda during Netanyahu's four-day visit to the Netherlands and
Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
