<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Opposes Unbalanced Peace in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa today expressed his country's strong opposition
against an unbalanced peace in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival in Kuwait for a short visit, Moussa told
reporters that there would be "no unbalanced peace in the Middle
East benefiting one single party." He said that the Middle East
peace process was a comprehensive peace march grouping all Arab
parties.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on a proposal by Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu to start "final status" talks with the
Palestinians similar to the 1979 Egyptian-Israeli Camp David
talks.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that Arab's active diplomacy was aimed at
countering the Israeli-triggered setback in the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He said "preserving the Middle East peace process was the
responsibility of all."
</P>
<P>
"Our efforts spring from our keenness on solving the crisis
the peace process has come to due to Israel's actions," the
Egyptian minister said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt hosted a foreign ministerial meeting of the 22-member
Arab League on March 30 when the ministers decided to reactivate
the Arab economic boycott of Israel and stop the normalization
process with the Jewish state in response to the start of
construction of 6,500 new Jewish homes in Israeli-annexed Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also said his Kuwait tour was aimed at discussing ways
to promote bilateral relations and coordination with regard to
vital issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
But he did not give details as to what specific matters he
would discuss with the Kuwaiti leaders.
</P>
<P>
Later today, he is expected to hold talks with Kuwaiti acting
Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad
Al-Jaber Al-Sabah. 
</P>
