<HEADLINE> Philippine House to Hammer Out Final Stand on Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine House Speaker Jose de
Venecia will preside over a closed-door caucus of congressmen
tonight to hammer out a final stand on individual and corporate
income tax measures.
</P>
<P>
According to the Philippine News Agency, the caucus will be
multi-party and will be composed of senior House leaders and some
junior congressmen.
</P>
<P>
"After the meeting tonight, we shall have arrived at a
consensus on the ranges of tax exemptions," the speaker stressed.
</P>
<P>
The House has not been able to approve the said last phase of
the Comprehensive Tax Reform Package due to differences on how
much is the best tax relief both for the Filipino laborers and for
the government.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund, which was satisfied with the
fast economic growth of the Philippines, has said it would allow
the country to graduate from the organization if it could finish
the last phase of its tax reform by June.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia said that despite the fact that the congressmen tend
to give the highest tax exemptions they could give, they would
also consider revenues for the government.
</P>
<P>
The House is battling for a 184,000-peso (7,000 U.S. dollars)
tax relief from the current 56,000 pesos (2,100 U.S. dollars) for
a family of six. However, the Presidential Palace said this is
sacrificing revenues for the government.
</P>
<P>
Speaker De Venecia expressed confidence that before the lower
House resumes regular sessions on April 21, they will have come up
with a compromise.  
</P>
</TEXT>
