<HEADLINE> Iraq Defends Flight of Pilgrims to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 10 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi official argued today that
the flight carrying 104 Iraqi pilgrims to Saudi port city of
Jedda Wednesday was a "purely humanitarian and religious one."
</P>
<P>
Nazar Hamdoun, Iraqi permanent representative to the U.N., was
quoted by the Iraqi News Agency as saying that the U.N. Security
Council resolutions make no reference at all of forbidding Iraq to
run overseas flights, so there was no violation of the
U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the U.N. Security Council will have regard for the
feelings of Iraqis and Muslims all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Hamdoun pointed out that Iraq has attempted over the past years
to get the U.N. consent to running flights to carry Iraqi pilgrims
to Saudi Arabia. But the U.N. Sanctions Committee has failed to
approve such flights, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Saudi authorities admitted the Iraqi pilgrims
without any objection to the flight that carried them to Jedda,
adding that the plane already returned to Baghdad, the capital of
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi flight carrying pilgrims from Baghdad to Jedda
provoked Wednesday a storm of legal debate at the U.N. Security
council.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Sanctions Committee will hold today a formal meeting
to discuss the Iraqi flight to Jedda. The meeting will be followed
by a U.N. Security council consultation session on the same
topic.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed trade and air embargo on Iraq following its
invasion of Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
