<HEADLINE> Kohl, Chirac Stick to Euro Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and
French President Jacques Chirac have expressed their firm
determination to hold to both the qualifying criteria and the 1999
start date for the single European currency -- the euro.
</P>
<P>
A German government spokesman Peter Hausman said that during
their informal meeting Wednesday night in Bonn, both Kohl and
Chirac stressed that any change in the euro criteria and its
timetable would not be allowed.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also agreed on close cooperation between Bonn
and Paris in a bid to bring the Inter-Governmental Conference on
European Union reform to a successful end during the EU's mid-July
summit in Amsterdam. They agreed to hold several meetings before
the summit.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Kohl and Chirac also shared wide common
views on international issues including the NATO eastward
expansion. Kohl will also discuss the issue with Russian President
Boris Yeltsin, who will visit Germany on April 17.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders' informal meeting was held over dinner
Wednesday night in Kohl's personal residence in the chancellery
garden. But they did not have a press conference after the
meeting. 
