<HEADLINE> China Becomes World's Second Biggest Commercial Arbitration Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- China has become the second
largest commercial arbitration center in the world, with more than
800 cases concerning foreign nations being reviewed yearly by
China's main commercial arbitration institutions, an arbitration
official said today.
</P>
<P>
According to Cheng Dejun, vice-chairman of both the China
International Economic and Trade Arbitration Committee and the
China Maritime Arbitration Commission, a total of over 5,000 cases
have been heard by his institutions since the 1950s, when China
first became involved in this practice.
</P>
<P>
Cheng, who is now attending the 32nd conference of the
International Chamber of Commerce, said that in recent years the
amount of disputed money has been steadily increased, with the
highest sum of one case exceeding 60 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the disputes are concentrated in such fields as
cooperation or joint venture contracts, compensation trade,
finance, and real estate," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that with China's increasingly important role in the
international trade and economic affairs, his organizations have
established cooperation ties with more than ten other
international arbitration institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
