<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Social Security System Benefiting Poor Urban Residents (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- More than one million needy
residents in Chinese cities have benefited from a new social
security system, a spokesman of the Civil Affairs Ministry said
today.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March, some 156 cities, or about one-fourth of
the country's total, have introduced the "lowest income level
social security system," which was launched to supplement the
traditional social relief system, step up reforms of state-run
enterprises and improve social stability, said Yang Jianchang,
spokesman of the ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said those cities provide 200 million yuan (about 24 million
US dollars) each year to help the poor, and more than one million
people had been helped by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Before the implementation of the new system, the country's
social relief was limited to people who did not have a stable
income, were incapable of working or had no legal financial
providers.
</P>
<P>
But in recent years, a new poverty-stricken group came to be
formed by the unemployed people and laid-off workers from the
bankrupt enterprises, enterprises with suspended production or
that had reduced operations as well as retirees and the jobless,
Yang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that there are about 13 million needy urban residents
around the country.
</P>
<P>
"The new system is a major reform of the original social
relief system of the poor urban residents," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, the government should provide basic living
expenses for those poor urban residents whose income is below the
lowest set level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
