<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Tops 127 Yen in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar today topped 127
yen for the first time since August 1992 amid expectations that
U.S. interest rates will rise again.
</P>
<P>
The Dollar was traded as high as 127.17 yen, marking the
56-month high in early deals on the Tokyo market.
</P>
<P>
It was changing hands at 126.09-12 yen at 5 p.m., down from
127.07-10 yen at 9 a.m., and from 126.85-95 yen in New York
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
dealers said the dollar is no longer likely to race far ahead
as players liquidated their long, or overbrought, dollar positions
on comments by Japanese high-ranking officials suggesting possible
market intervention by the Bank of Japan. 
</P>
