<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Congress Issues Whip to Defeat UF Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- India's Congress Party today
issued a whip to its MPs to defeat the motion of confidence to be
moved by Prime Minister Deve Gowda in the Lower House of
parliament tomorrow, the Congress sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The whip directed all party members to support the stand of the
Congress leadership to withdraw support to the United Front (UF)
government on March 30.
</P>
<P>
The Congress's whip was issued following the failure of two
rounds of talks between the UF and the Congress since last
evening. The congress demand for a Congress-led coalition to be
headed by its president, Sitaram Kesri, to the change of the
United Front leadership in the talks was rejected by UF leaders.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the conclusion of the second round of talks, the
Congress Working Committee (CWC), the highest policy-making body
of the party, and the UF Standing Committee were meeting here to
review the latest situation.
</P>
<P>
The government sources said that some proposals have been given
to the Congress negotiators for consideration by the party and the
UF is expecting a reply from the Congress by this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
To a query, Congress negotiator S. Pawar did not rule out the
possibility of a third round of talks between the negotiators.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary party of the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP),
the biggest opposition party in the country, which met here today,
left it to its leader, A.B. Vajpayee to decide the party's
strategy on the motion of confidence tomorrow since the situation
was fluid.
</P>
<P>
The 10-month old UF government needs the support of 77 members
in the parliament to ensure its survival during the confidence
vote tomorrow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
