<HEADLINE> FedEx Service to China Enhanced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The US-based Federal Express
(FedEx) has announced the expansion to four direct flights weekly
in its existing US-China and China-Asia service.
</P>
<P>
There were formerly three flights each week. The extension of
flight service further enhances the connectivity for imports and
exports between China and Asia, and China and the United States,
according to a FedEx official.
</P>
<P>
John Quinn, vice president for China and Mid-Pacific Regions,
says FedEx has "aggressive expansion plans for China to add new
service destinations."
</P>
<P>
The number of destinations has increased from 60 in September
1996 to the present 73, and will be further expanded over the next
five years, according to Quinn.
</P>
<P>
FedEx's China-US flight service was launched in March 1996, and
in the following September was extended to FedEx's Asia Pacific
Hub in Subic Bay, the Philippines, linking China to its extensive
AsiaOne network which now connects 13 major cities in Asia for
overnight deliveries.  
</P>
