<HEADLINE> Social Security System Benefiting Poor Urban Residents (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The system has a wider coverage and is more efficient than
before, said Yang, who added that the financial aid provided to
poor residents, ranging from 70 yuan to 230 yuan a month, is set
by city governments in accordance with the local economic
development and per capital living standard.
</P>
<P>
The program was first launched in the country's largest city of
Shanghai in 1993, and spread to 12 cities by 1995. The 156 cities
where the system was implemented are in 24 provinces, autonomous
regions and municipalities. Small towns in 56 counties have also
introduced the system.
</P>
<P>
"The rapid establishment of the system shows the great concern
of the local governments," said an official with the Social Relief
Department of the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Yang said that Tianjin Municipality, Shanxi, Sichuan and
Guizhou provinces, Tibet, and the Ningxia Hui and Xinjiang Uygur
autonomous regions are planning to use the new plan.
</P>
<P>
He said that the ministry will work diligently to spread the
system to more cities across China, while trying to further
improve the system during the drafting of the Social Relief Law.
</P>
<P>
China has made great progress in its poverty-relief work in
rural areas during the past two decades, with the number of needy
people in these regions declining by 10 million a year. There are
still 58 million poor rural residents in China.
</P>
<P>
The lowest income social security system for poor rural
residents, launched by the ministry in 1995, has already been
adopted in more than 130 counties. 
</P>
