<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Ease Fuel Scarcity With Oil Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
ordered the release of federal reserve as part of the interim
measures to alleviate the lingering fuel scarcity that has been
bitting the country harder in the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The government has also mandated the Military Task Force on
Petroleum Distribution to dispatch soldiers to ensure prompt
distribution of the fuel, according to local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
The decisions were made at a meeting between the chief of
defense, the petroleum resources minister, top officials of the
Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC) and managing
directors of refineries, held at the Defense Headquarters here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The need for soldiers to monitor the distribution is to ensure
that the fuel is diverted from depots to filling stations instead
of unknown destinations, the reports said, quoting Director of
Defense Information Colonel Godwin Ugbo.
</P>
<P>
With the meeting, which was convened at the instance of Head
of State General Sani Abacha, the even supply of fuel would be
normalized from today, he added.
</P>
<P>
The current fuel crisis, triggered by the failure in domestic
production, started in Lagos, the nation's economic center, and
neighboring states in the southwest three weeks ago. It spread up
to the north and affected the federal capital of Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Lagos have been much limited in their movement
these days and the metropolis has become quite quiet as the
number of vehicles seen in the streets has been reduced greatly.
</P>
<P>
The fuel scarcity has also driven bus fares and food prices
high in cities.
</P>
<P>
Worried by spreading fuel crisis, Abacha called state
administrators and oil industry officials to the capital on Monday
to find a solution.
</P>
<P>
He also ordered the importation of more fuel to end the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to Petroleum Minister Dan Etete, all vacations and
overseas tours by top officials of the ministry have been
cancelled so that they can come together to fashion a solution.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Lagos State Administrator Colonel Mohammed
Marwa said the government would also move to repair the country's
ailing refineries, which are the fundamental reason behind the
outbreak of fuel crisis from time to time in this largest oil
producing country in Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
