<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full-Time Work Declines to Lowest Level in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Unemployment in Australia
slipped slightly to 8.7 percent in March compared with 8.8 percent
in February, but the full-time work declined to the lowest level
in almost 18 months.
</P>
<P>
An Australian Bureau of Statistics survey, released today,
showed that employment fell by 33,900 in March, seasonally
adjusted, following a decline in full-time work to the lowest
since October 1995.
</P>
<P>
Employment Minister Amanda Vanstone admitted the fall in
employment was regrettable but pointed to a positive outlook for
economic growth and improved prospects for jobs growth.
</P>
<P>
"The economic signs point to a very positive outlook, the
government is confident that as we have also got the lowest
interest rates and home mortgage rates we have had since 1973,"
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
However, Opposition employment spokesman Martin Ferguson said,
"It was the prime minister who said that 12 months was the point
to measure his performance, now the first year of Howard's prime
ministership had been a disaster for Australians wanting a job."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
