<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africans Allowed to Collect Crayfish in Bags </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 10 (Xinhua) -- South Africans have been
allowed today by the Environmental Affairs and Tourism Ministry
to collect crayfish on the beaches of the Cape West Coast in
Western Cape Province.
</P>
<P>
The permit followed a tour to Elands Bay on Wednesday by
Deputy Environment Affairs Minister Peter Mokaba and an African
National Congress Member of Parliament Tony Yengeni, said local
press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Mokaba said the public had been allowed to collect crayfish in
bays, not in trucks or vans, for their own consumption, but not
for selling.
</P>
<P>
More than 1200 tons of crayfish "walked out" of the sea onto
the beaches at Elands Bay over the weekend to escape the toxic
red tide which depletes oxygen levels in the waters.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time in the past two weeks that a huge number
of crayfish crawled from the sea. About 60 tons of crayfish
"walked" out of the sea onto the beaches in the region shortly
before Easter.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people descended on the beaches to collect the
unexpected delicacy, despite the legal permit that only four
crayfish per person could be taken away.
</P>
<P>
However, the police set the roadblocks in the past few days to
check the traffic coming from the area, confiscating crayfish
caught in the roadblocks, and arrest those who transport and
sell the crayfish illegally.
</P>
<P>
People traveling to the Elands Bay were also warned by the
police that if they aimed to collect crayfish, their vehicles
would be searched when they left the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
