<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Further Reform and Opening-up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing
said here today that China will expand its reform and opening up
and take a still more active part in broadening and deepening
international labor specialization and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the plenary meeting of the 32nd World Congress
of the International Chamber of Commerce (ICC), Li said that
infrastructure construction will still be the focus of China's
reform and opening up as well as the country's use of overseas
investment.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, China had attracted a total of 175 billion
US dollars in foreign funds, with half invested in infrastructure
construction. This field had drawn about 10 percent of the 177
billion US dollar direct investment.
</P>
<P>
In the coming five years, Li said, China will spend on
infrastructure buildup even more than the 280 billion US dollar
amount mentioned in the World Bank report.
</P>
<P>
Li noted the Chinese government will continue improving its
environment for foreign investment, and that China has achieved
the convertibility of Renminbi yuan under the current account so
as to guarantee the repatriation of the foreign investors' profits.
</P>
<P>
China will adopt measures that are in line with the
international norms to accelerate the building of a legal system
so as to maintain the order of competition in its internal market,
bring the government's actions into full view and upgrade its
decision-making efficiency, Li said.
</P>
<P>
He said that China will do more to strengthen its service,
administration and supervision of the foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
While making proper use of credit to speed up infrastructure
construction, the vice-premier said, China will increase the
proportion of direct overseas investment, and continue the
experiments in such investment modes as BOT (building, operation
and transfer).
</P>
<P>
Li said the Chinese government will provide foreign investors
with easy access to market information and offer preferential
treatment to foreign-funded enterprises gradually. Moreover, he
added, it will encourage competition, oppose monopoly, and combine
foreign investment, new technology introduction and acceleration
of readjusting China's industrial structure.
</P>
<P>
China will encourage foreign investment in the comprehensive
agricultural development and resource use, and also high-tech
industries, according to Li. China will also actively attract
foreign investment in the central and western regions.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging that China needs the world and the world needs
China, Li said cooperation on the basis of equality results in
mutual profits, whereas friction and confrontation bring losses to
both sides.
</P>
<P>
Li pledged China's firm opposition to any conduct which is
unfair, discriminatory to China and has a protectionist nature,
such as anti-dumping and unilateral limitations.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he reiterated that China, as always, holds a positive
attitude in the accession to the World Trade Organization, but not
at the cost of making a commitment that is beyond its capability.
</P>
<P>
China is now a developing country, and still will be one by the
year 2010, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Also at the meeting, Chinese Minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Wu Yi delivered a speech on the globalization
of trade.
</P>
<P>
Delegates attending the meeting discussed, among others,
China's commercial and investment environment, the solution to
Asia's business disputes and the economic growth of Shanghai and
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The two-day 32nd World Congress of ICC ended here this
afternoon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
