<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Hyacinth Used to Produce Biogas in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Water hyacinth choking water
bodies in Uganda has found an economic use to produce biogas,
the local newspaper "the Monitor" reported today.
</P>
<P>
A biogas manufacturing unit in Luzira Upper Prison, central
Uganda, put shredded weed into a digester container with cow dungs
and water. The mixed mass is generated by bacterium.
</P>
<P>
Among the bacterium, hydrolysis degrades the weed,
acidogenesis produces acetic acids, fat, sugars, methanol and
hydrogen, methanogenesis produces biogas with carbon dioxide and
hydrogen.
</P>
<P>
Biogas is produced within five days, said Anastase Rwigyema,
an engineer of the biogas producing unit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
