<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Praises NAM Ministerial Meeting in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign Minister
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi today described the Non-Aligned Movement
(NAM) Foreign Ministers' Meeting in New Delhi as a success.
</P>
<P>
He said several resolutions were adopted including the ones
calling NAM member countries to freeze diplomatic ties with
Israel, restructuring and reformation in the United Nations (UN)
and South-South cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"The resolution calling for freezing ties with Israel is
something which has never been done before by NAM and is an
important step," he said on his return from New Delhi where he
among more than 70 counterparts attended the two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
On whether NAM member countries having ties with Tel Aviv would
enforce the resolution as agreed to, he said "they will not
enhance existing ties."
</P>
<P>
Regarding the UN reformation, the minister said many NAM member
countries expressed their interest in the proposal of the UN
General Assembly President Razali Ismail on expanding the
membership of the Security Council and on other related
reformation.
</P>
<P>
Razali, who is a Malaysian, tabled the proposal to increase the
number of permanent and non permanent members at a UN General
Assembly session on March 20.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said that since NAM member countries wanted the matter
to be discussed first, the decision was made to hold follow-up
discussions during the UN General Assembly in September which will
be attended by NAM foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
"The NAM meeting has agreed that any decision relating to the
restructuring of the Security Council should not be made at
present. On the other hand, there should be a general agreement
first," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the stalled West Asia peace process following
Israel's move to expand Jewish settlement, Abdullah regretted the
U.S. action in exercising its veto power twice against the
resolution condemning Israel on the matter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
