<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Singapore Want Closer Relations: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Singapore have
agreed to develop closer and stronger relations in future in their
common interest, Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi
said today.
</P>
<P>
He said he and his Singapore counterpart S. Jayakumar had the
common view during their talks on Monday before they attended the
ASEAN Foreign Ministers' informal meeting in New Delhi where they
both attended the 12th Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) Foreign
Ministers' conference.
</P>
<P>
Their bilateral meeting in New Delhi was the first after the
diplomatic furor between the two countries following Senior
Minister Lee Kuan Yew's remarks about Malaysia's Johor state close
to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Lee apologized following protests by Malaysians and his apology
was accepted by the Malaysian government.
</P>
<P>
"The spontaneous meeting lasted 15 minutes," the Malaysian
minister told reporters upon his return from India, adding he and
Jayakumar agreed that both countries should work towards closer
and stronger relations although it would take time following the
unhappy episode.
</P>
<P>
"As foreign ministers we need to manage the relations well and
ensure that future relations will be more sound and closer for our
mutual benefits," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We understand that relations between Malaysia and Singapore
are not frozen or severed and hence the ties should continue," he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
