<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 09:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait's money supply in its broad term rose
by 81.9 million Kuwaiti Dinars (270 million U.S. dollars) in
January from December of 1996 to reach 7.4127 billion dinars
(24.46 billion dollars), a monthly bulletin by the Central Bank
of Kuwait (CBK) said today.
</P>
<P>
It said the increase in money supply was mainly due to the
increase of deposits in local commercial banks which stood at
64.1 million dinars (211.5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
It said the total deposits at the CBK decreased by 33.7
million dinars (111.2 million dollars) during January to 1.0833
billion dianrs (3.575 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Foreign currency deposits of local banks also rose by 39
million dinars (128.7 million dollars) in January to 1.4465
billion dinars (4.773 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli Finance Ministry is ready to make
sweeping cuts in health care and education spending, in addition
to a 7.2 billion shekels (2.1 billion U.S. dollars) cut in the
country's 1997 budget, reported The Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing State Budget Director Ran Kroll indicated before
leaving his post that there is waste in education. The Treasury
said reductions can be made in teachers' non-teaching hours.
</P>
<P>
In the field of health care, the Treasury wants to rethink
the calculations for beds and patients, and is also unhappy with
the extent of various religious subsidies.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Cisco System, the international leader in
Internet networking solutions, will assign its newly opened
research and development center in Netanya, north of Tel Aviv,
with the task of developing the next generation of Internet
technology, reported The Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
A senior official of the U.S. San Jose-based company, which
has an annual turnover of more than 4 billion U.S. dollars,
said that Israel has "an excellent pool of people that you can't
find in Silicon Valley" of the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The rapid growth of the chip design industry in Israel in
the last few years has proven the commitment of this country to
be a leader rather than a follower in the (information
technologies) market," he said.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Hassan Khalilian, advisor to Iranian Interior
Minister Ali Mohammad Besharati, said here today that taxi fares
will increase by 10 percent from April 21 after a fuel price rise
last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He warned that taxi drivers who violate the decision by
charging above 10 percent of the present fares would face fines.
</P>
<P>
Buses, both operating inside and outside cities, would have to
stick to the present fares until the decision goes into effect on
April 21.
</P>
<P>
There are about 3 million cars and 100,000 taxi cars in the
Iranian capital city of Tehran with a population of about 10
million.
</P>
<P>
Observers said that the government has to set the ceiling of
price rise because prices of many products and services have
already increased shortly after the rise of fuel price by a
quarter last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian complains that the taxi fare has actually risen by
20 to 25 percent in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
Iran raised the fuel prices by 50 percent last year and 100
percent the previous year. The move triggered some protests and
demonstrations from people who complain a lot about the runaway
inflation.
</P>
<P>
Iran's central bank said the inflation rate stood at 26.1
percent during the first 11 months of the last Iranian calendar
year ending on March 20, 1997. But observers here say that the
inflation is about 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under Iran's second five-year development plan (1995-1999),
prices of oil products will be increased slightly every year.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices in oil-rich Iran are still among the lowest in the
world. It costs about four U.S. dollars to fill a car with super
petrol.
</P>
</TEXT>
