<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fuzhou's Changle International Airport to Be Put Into Regular Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Changle International Airport of
Fuzhou, capital of east China's Fujian Province, is scheduled to
start regular operations on June 23, local sources said.
</P>
<P>
Fuzhou, which looks to Taiwan across the Taiwan Straits, is an
important place for exchange of mail and shipping services across
the straits and has been chosen to pilot direct air and shipping
service between Taiwan and interior areas of China.
</P>
<P>
The city's air service volume has been growing at an annual
rate of 31 percent over past years as the city has seen a rapid
expansion of its export-oriented economy. The existing Yixu
airport, which is used for both military and civilian purposes,
can not meet the new development demands.
</P>
<P>
The building of the Changle airport is not only a strategic
step taken to expand economic development of the southeastern
coastal areas, but also conducive to an accelerated availability
of the exchange of mail service, trade, air and shipping services
across the straits, said Wang Yingquan, general manager of Changle
International Airport Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The newly-built airport cost 3.23 billion yuan and began
construction in June of 1994. The airport, with a terminal floor
space of 137,000 sq m, is designed to accommodate large-capacity
passengers planes such as Boeing 747-400s, and handle 6.5 million
passengers and 200,000 tons of cargo a year.
</P>
<P>
Before starting regular service in June, the airport will
conduct trial operations on May 10, according to the general
manager. 
</P>
</TEXT>
