<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, India, Sri Lanka to Form Growth Triangle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Thailand, India and Sri Lanka
have agreed in principle to form a new growth triangle of
cooperation to strengthen tripartite links in political, economic
and cultural activities, Thai Foreign Ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
The idea was raised by Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab Chaiyasan
at a meeting with Indian officials in New Delhi where he attended
the non-aligned movement.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was in line with Thailand's new "looking west"
policy aimed at strengthening ties with countries located to its
west, said Kobsak Chutikul, director general of the Economic
Department.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will seek stronger ties with the other countries
through the proposed triangle, currently known as the IST (India,
Sri Lanka and Thailand), after it is formed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that senior officials from the three
countries will meet within the next three months to discuss
details of a pact to form the growth triangle.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank is also conducting a study on the
tripartite forum to determine the cooperation areas of mutual
interest.
</P>
<P>
Prachuab said that India's "looking east" policy fits perfectly
with Thailand's "looking west" policy.
</P>
<P>
Trade between India and Thailand has grown at an impressive
rate, from 400 million US dollars in 1992 to 915 million US
dollars in 1995, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has become the eighth largest investor in India, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Thailand and Sri Lanka has been limited and
complementary, Kobsak said, adding that about 80 percent of the
bilateral trade between Thailand and Sri Lanka has been related to
gem processing.
</P>
<P>
After the triangle is formed, the three countries would be able
to enhance cooperation in various fields, like fishery,
technology, agriculture, transport, culture and investment, the
official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
