<HEADLINE> Palestinians Engaged in Anti-Israeli Stone Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Several hundred Palestinian
youths resumed stone-throwing and fire bomb battle to protest
against the Israeli troops in Hebron this morning.
</P>
<P>
The fight is taking place at the border area in the largely
Palestinian self-rule city in the West Bank, according to a report
of the JMCC, an East Jerusalem-based Palestinian press service.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli soldiers who are armed to the teeth responded with
rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
During the clashes, three Palestinian stone-throwers were so
far injured, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Street battles between Palestinian youths and Israeli troops
have been continuing for three days running today.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have deadlocked and violence
has erupted since Israel launched construction for the new Jewish
housing project of 6,500 homes in East Jerusalem last month.
</P>
<P>
Three Palestinians were killed, and more than 100 Palestinians
were wounded in Hebron Tuesday. The clashes, the fiercest since
January's Hebron redeployment agreement, raged for five hours. The
violence broke out when one of two Israeli religious students
opened fire with his M-16 automatic rifle, killing one
Palestinian and wounding another.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's confrontations followed a funeral of one of the
three Palestinians killed by Israeli troops Tuesday. A total of
32 Palestinians were wounded by Israeli rubber bullets and tear
gas. Two of them suffered serious wounds.
</P>
<P>
Nader Saed, 24, died after he was struck in the eye by a
rubber bullet fired by an Israeli soldier at a close range.
</P>
<P>
People attending his funeral shouted "Izzadin," the name of
Hamas military wing. Others shouted "Revenge." Palestinian
policemen also attended the funeral and fired in the air as
Saed's body covered in a Palestinian national flag, was buried.
</P>
</TEXT>
