<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Economy Up 16.4 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen, China's pioneer in
reform and opening up to the outside world, saw its economy grow
16.4 percent in 1996 than in 1995, with its GDP reaching 95
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The city's statistics bureau said that the growth rate was 6.7
percentage points higher than the national average in the year.
</P>
<P>
The high economic speed was achieved despite a deceleration of
its foreign trade business. The city's foreign trade volume grew
only 0.7 percent, while the rate was 20.3 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The city economy had been galloping at a yearly average of 34
percent since it was granted the status of a special economic zone
in 1980. Booming foreign trade had been an important part of the
city's economic takeoff.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said that the city's quick economic growth has not
been accompanied with a high inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
Its retail price index rose 3.9 percent over 1995, 2.2
percentage points lower than the national average.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
