<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Urges Small Firms to Produce High-value Added </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today urges the country's small and medium enterprises (SMEs) to
transform from the typically low-end, low-value intermediate
processors of raw materials to producers of high-value added
products.
</P>
<P>
"This challenge is not beyond our capacity to meet," Ramos said
during the presentation of Bank Excellence Awards of the Guarantee
Fund for SMEs this morning in the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
He said many of the world's leading multinational companies,
including Sony of Japan, Microsoft of the United States and
Samsung of South Korea, started out as SMEs.
</P>
<P>
Ramos stressed that 90 percent of the country's enterprises, 40
percent of the manufacturing sector's labor force is employed by
SMEs and 24 percent of the value-added products produced in the
sector is attributable to SMEs.
</P>
<P>
The rising strength of the SME sector validates the economic
gains that his administration has strived for these past few
years, he said.
</P>
<P>
The President also called on the Guarantee Fund for SMEs to
pursue a new and larger role -- as advocates of local SMEs and
entrepreneurs, who are potential world-class winners.
</P>
<P>
The Guarantee Fund is a government credit guarantee program
designed to resources cash resources of lending institutions in
support for SMEs.
</P>
<P>
Under the fund, stronger entities in the economy, such as banks
in particular, have shared their strength and resources with the
smaller players, he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the last five years, bank loans to the SMEs with the
support of the fund have increased from 1.5 billion pesos (57
million US dollars) in 1992 to more than 5 billion pesos (190
million US dollars) by the end of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
