<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 08:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Asks Europe to Take "Even-Handed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu has asked the Europeans not to harbor any
unrealistic illusions about their role in the Middle East peace
process on the eve of his visit to the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu left Israel late Wednesday night for the Hague of
the Netherlands, current European Union (EU) rotating president,
according to a report of the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
The premier is scheduled to meet today with Dutch Prime
Minister Wim Kok and Foreign Minister Hans van Mierlo to
exchange views on the crisis-ridden Middle East peace
process. He will also visit Italy before returning home Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's visit came at a time when EU officials stepped up
pressure for a greater role of the 15-nation bloc in the Mideast
peace-making. They said the escalating violence in the region
would be on the agenda during Netanyahu's visit to the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel appears in no way to be inclined to make such
an offer. In his address to an international mayoral conference
in Jerusalem Wednesday evening, Netanyahu charged that one of
the obstacles in the peace process has been an European bias
toward the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He reminded the EU that it is the United States who should be
the center of facilitating negotiations. He added that any
agreement between the Israelis and Palestinians can only be
signed with the assistance of the U.S. as "a facilitator."
</P>
<P>
"I think (the U.S.) contribution is absolutely crucial," the
prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
"There are some who think that Europe can play it, (and) some
who think Russia can play it, (but) too many cooks spoil the
broth. The one cook that we need at this stage, and I think
there's an agreement on the Palestinian and Arab side in general
on this, is the United States. So it's necessary, and I think it
might be needed very soon," added Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
He has all along strongly criticized the European-brokered Oslo
Accords, saying it was a bad agreement and he would do his best to
offset the bad effects of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians say Netanyahu's proposal to embark on
"express way" in the peace talks is aimed at bypassing the Oslo
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told the mayors, including some from Europe, that
although Europe can not play a leading, but can still play an
important role in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that Europe should do two things. one is, as it
economically committed, to participate in many projects,
especially to help the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
On the other, Netanyahu explained that Europe has excellent
relations with Israel and Arab countries and traditionally it
has better relations in some cases with Arab countries than with
the Jewish state. Just because of that, he said, if Europe
introduces what he called "a more balanced approach" to the
question of how to treat the various issues in the peace
process, this will create a more balanced approach in the Arab
world.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that "a more even-handed policy" will create
"a more realistic expectations," and thus the gap between the
Israelis and Palestinians will be bridged into a final
settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
