<HEADLINE> EU Team To Inspect Fish Plants In Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) is
expected to dispatch a two-man veterinary delegation in the
middle of next month to inspect all fish processing factories in
Tanzania to evaluate their capacity and hygiene.
</P>
<P>
EU Principal Administrator Christian Herbin made this
disclosure here on Wednesday, saying that the EU mission would
inspect fish processing facilities in Dar es Salaam and Mwannza
regions in a very strict manner and according to the EU regulations.
</P>
<P>
The delegates would examine hygiene of vessels, loading of
fish, transport of fish to processing facilities, refrigeration
and transport to Europe.
</P>
<P>
Herbin cautioned that if the delegates would not be satisfied
with the situation, Tanzania would be banned from exporting fish
to European markets.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the EU suspended importation of fish fillets from
Tanzania after it was found that they were contaminated by virus
dangerous to consumers' health.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister for Natural Resources and Tourism Zakia
Meghji visited Mwanza fish processing factories last week and
directed the factory owners to improve sanitation, warning that
factories failing to meet the accepted standards would be closed
and banned from exporting fish fillets to European markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
