<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans to End Asset, Capital Check in 3-4 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- China will complete an asset and
capital audit of the urban collective enterprises in three to four
years, according to an on-going national meeting here.
</P>
<P>
The move is to urge the collective enterprises, an inseparable
force of the Chinese economy, to improve their management, and is
also a large-scale comprehensive investigation of the country's
economic situation and economic strength, according to Chinese
vice-minister of finance Zhang Youcai.
</P>
<P>
The check-up covers all collective enterprises and units
registered with the industrial and commercial administration
departments at all levels over the next three or four years, an
official at the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
First piloted in 226 cities and prefectures last year, the
check-up covered a total of 13,000 urban collective enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary statistics show that the enterprises checked had a
combined 139.3 billion yuan in assets and 112 billion yuan in
liabilities at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The checking effort this year will be expanded to over ten
percent of the enterprises in all areas and sectors, according to
official arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Official records show that China had a total of 495,000 urban
collective enterprises at the end of 1996, including 210,000
commericial and trading businesses, and 146,000 industrial firms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
