<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taxi Fares in Iran to Increase by 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Hassan Khalilian, advisor to
Iranian Interior Minister Ali Mohammad Besharati, said here today
that taxi fares will increase by 10 percent from April 21 after a
fuel price rise last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He warned that taxi drivers who violate the decision by
charging above 10 percent of the present fares would face fines.
</P>
<P>
Buses, both operating inside and outside cities, would have to
stick to the present fares until the decision goes into effect on
April 21.
</P>
<P>
There are about 3 million cars and 100,000 taxi cars in the
Iranian capital city of Tehran with a population of about 10
million.
</P>
<P>
Observers said that the government has to set the ceiling of
price rise because prices of many products and services have
already increased shortly after the rise of fuel price by a
quarter last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
An Iranian complains that the taxi fare has actually risen by
20 to 25 percent in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
Iran raised the fuel prices by 50 percent last year and 100
percent the previous year. The move triggered some protests and
demonstrations from people who complain a lot about the runaway
inflation.
</P>
<P>
Iran's central bank said the inflation rate stood at 26.1
percent during the first 11 months of the last Iranian calendar
year ending on March 20, 1997. But observers here say that the
inflation is about 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under Iran's second five-year development plan (1995-1999),
prices of oil products will be increased slightly every year.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices in oil-rich Iran are still among the lowest in the
world. It costs about four U.S. dollars to fill a car with super
petrol. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
