<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serial Quakes in Northwest China to Be Deciphered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Seismological Bureau of
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region decided to set
up a provisional seismological observatory in Jiashi county, to
better monitor, predict, and study the earthquakes there.
</P>
<P>
Successive earthquakes estimated at over 6.0 on the Richter
scale hit the same county twice over the past 36 years and this
has drawn great attention.
</P>
<P>
This January 21, two quakes at 6.4 and 6.3 took place in Jiashi
county, on March 1, a quake at 6.0, and another two at 6.3 and 6.4
on April 6, struck the county, resulting in heavy losses and
casualties. More than 2,400 after-shocks have occurred since then,
including nine at over 5.0 on the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
Same thing occurred in 1961. A quake at 6.8 hit the county on
April 1, and another two at 6.4 and 6.8 took place in the county
on April 4 and April 14, respectively. After-shocks continued for
20 months.
</P>
<P>
It is rare in seismological history to have so many strong
quakes hitting the same place in such short intervals, said Su
Naiqin, associate research fellow with the bureau.
</P>
<P>
The major difference lies in that the quake magnitude of the
1961 series weakened rapidly, while this time there are no obvious
signs for the quakes to decline in terms of magnitude and
after-shocks, Su noted. the epicenter shifted 80 to 90 km westward
this time, and the quake activities have no definite moving
direction.
</P>
<P>
"Most quakes in Xinjiang took place in surface fault zones, but
this time we didn't find evident geological faults," Su Said.
</P>
<P>
Seismologists at home and abroad showed serious concern for the
natural phenomenon of serial quakes, and voiced different
views. But it is still a long way to go before the secret can be
decoded through joint efforts of scientists worldwide, Su said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
