<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Outstanding Artist Passes Away </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Wu Zuoren, 89, an outstanding
Chinese painter and fine arts educator, died of illness at 21:47
hours (Beijing) Wednesday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Wu was a member of the Standing Committee of the Sixth
National People's Congress, a member of the Standing Committee of
the Seventh National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference, and vice-chairman of the Fourth China
Federation of Literary and Art Circles.
</P>
<P>
Wu used to be vice-chairman of the Central Advisory Committee
of China Democratic League, chairman of the Chinese Artists
Association, and former president of Central Institute of Arts.
</P>
<P>
Wu graduated from Belgium's Royal Institute of Fine Arts with
honors of "laureate student" in 1935.
</P>
<P>
His works include "Boat Tracker," "Portrait of Qi Baishi,"
"Sanmen Gorge on Yellow River," and "Giant Pandas."
</P>
<P>
His "Grazing on Tibetan Grassland" done in the traditional
style of brush work won a gold medal at the Paris Grand Palace
Exhibition in 1982.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
