<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Income Gap Between Urban, Rural Residents Narrowing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The income gap between urban
and rural residents in south China's Guangdong Province has
continued to narrow, according to the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
But urban dwellers' per capita annual income remained 2.35
times that of farmers last year.
</P>
<P>
Government statistics show that famers scored a 7.6
percent increase in per capita income to hit 3,183.64 yuan last
year, with that of urban residents increasing by two percent to
7,488 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Official sources say that the income gap between city and
country dwellers was even bigger in 1995, and decreased marginally
a year later.
</P>
<P>
The southern Guangdong Province is the country's economic
powerhouse, and has seen a sustained economic growth in the past
few years.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that farmers have benefitted greatly from a
good harvest and price cuts of fertilizers and other agricultural
materials last year, which directly led to rapid rise in income.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the poor economic performance of some
state-owned enterprises also slowed the growth of income of city
residents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
