<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 07:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Refuses to Restore Security Cooperation with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) has rejected a request to restore security
cooperation with Israel to prevent further Israeli-Palestinian
violence, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The request was raised during a secret meeting Tuesday in
Gaza, which was attended by PNA President Yasser Arafat, Ami
Ayalon, head of the Israeli General Security Service,
representatives of the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) and
top Palestinian security officials.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian security chiefs in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip refused to restore security cooperation with Israel until
political contacts at all levels, including peace talks, were
resumed by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Following last month's suicide bombing attack in Tel Aviv,
which left three women dead and more than 40 others wounded, Israel
demanded a Palestinian crackdown on terrorism as a condition for
advancing the political process.
</P>
<P>
A senior Israeli diplomatic source said that there was a
Palestinian effort to calm the situation on the ground, but
security cooperation still remained unsatisfactory.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
said that the PNA was not doing enough to fight against terrorist
activity.
</P>
<P>
"While the Palestinian police were making some efforts to
stop street violence," said Mordechai. "The PNA was not yet
making real effort to halt terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Mordechai made the remarks after a meeting with top Israeli
security officials, including Ayalon and army chief of staff
Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, for a review of the situation in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli defense minister said that it was up to the PNA
leaders to do their best to fight against terrorist activity
before the two sides could start political contacts.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai told Israel Radio that the Palestinian violence was
on the increase in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, saying that the
Israeli army would take whatever measures necessary to protect
and maintain order.
</P>
<P>
He also admitted that there was not enough security
cooperation between the Israelis and Palestinians, especially the
cooperation in fighting against terrorist activity.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have been increasing in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip after two Jewish settlers Tuesday shot and killed one
Palestinian resident of Hebron and wounded two others.
</P>
<P>
Following the shooting incident, there have been serious
clashes Tuesday and Wednesday between Palestinian protesters and
Israeli soldiers in Hebron, during which two more Palestinians
were reportedly killed and more than 100 others injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
