<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Import Cargo Pilferage Rampant at Port Mombasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Importers using the port of
Mombasa are losing goods in an organized import cargo pilferage
racket, according to an East African Standard report today.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper which staged a six-hour stakeout at the
port last Saturday said that import cargo smugglers can steal any
type of goods from the port sheds.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that the most hit are importers of grains,
second-hand clothes, electronic goods among other things which
are stolen openly in the presence of Kenya Ports Authority
security personnel and port police.
</P>
<P>
Reporters of the paper witnessed import cargo stolen, saying
that the smugglers offered money to trailer drivers who allowed
them to load the stolen maize on top of other goods.
</P>
<P>
The trailers were then escorted by armed port police officers
to drive away and discharged the stolen goods outside the port.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Mombasa Port Police boss Philip Ndwiga as
confirming that the practice had been rampant at the port.
</P>
<P>
The police boss pointed out that the Port Authority had
mounted a major crackdown on the cargo pilfers since the massive
grain imports as relief food for the victims of the just ended
drought in the country started arriving at the port. 
</P>
</TEXT>
