<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China in Need of Huge Funds to Maintain Rapid Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- China's planned fixed asset
spending for the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000) totals
1.5 trillion US dollars, China Daily today quotes a senior Chinese
banking official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar at the ongoing 32nd Congress of the
International Chamber of Commerce, held in Shanghai, Wang Xuebing,
chairman and president of the Bank of China, said that most of the
needed funds will be raised in capital markets at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Enormous capital demand mainly comes from the need to sustain
a high rate of economic growth, improve infrastructure, and
rejuvenate the stagnant State sector, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank estimated that China will need 800 billion US
dollars during the next decade for its infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
If additional 80 billion US dollars is put into China's 1,000
largest State-owned enterprises, their current asset-liability
ratio of 60 percent will drop to the international standard of 45
percent, Wang predicted.
</P>
<P>
China will mainly explore its tremendous home-grown capital
resources derived from personal and public savings, which account
for 50 percent of China's national GDP.
</P>
<P>
The country has already applied 175 billion US dollars in a
wide array of projects over the past 18 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
