<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Needs More, Better Teachers for Primary, Middle Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- By the year 2000, China will need
nearly 10 million teachers with better educational backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
The State Education Commission (SEC) set this goal to be
attained by the end of this century. In a just-issued document, the
SEC said that China is lacking qualified teachers and the
distribution of teachers is not balanced among different areas, as
most teachers prefer cities to villages due to very different
teaching and living conditions.
</P>
<P>
The overall quality of teachers needs further improvement, said
the SEC in the document. According to the SEC, by the year
2000, over 95 percent of primary school teachers should have
received at least secondary school education.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of junior middle school teachers who have received
two-year college education should reach 80 percent, and about 70
percent of senior middle school teachers should receive four-year
college education.
</P>
<P>
The SEC also asked that teachers under age of 45 obtain the
required education diploma. By doing so, younger teachers will be
able to take greater responsibility in teaching.
</P>
<P>
The document further stipulates that the ratio of teachers
below the age of 45 who have senior professional titles should not
be less than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
An official from the SEC said that primary and junior middle
school teachers, rural school teachers, and backbone teachers will
be the focus of China's efforts to build a contingent of qualified
teachers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
