<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Students Protest Against New Fee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of students of
University of Zimbabwe yesterday in Harare protested peacefully
against the government's decision to withdraw half of student fees
it provided.
</P>
<P>
The students wanted loans to cover all expenses and agreed
that these must be re-paid once the receiving student graduates.
</P>
<P>
The students were also calling for an urgent review of the
country's tender system.
</P>
<P>
Singing revolutionary songs and monitored by uniformed
policemen, more than 2,000 students marched from the university
waving placards showing their dissatisfaction over both the new
policy on grant and loan packages and the indigenisation policy,
which they claimed had been "privatized and monopolized by
individuals."
</P>
<P>
In their petitions handed over to both Minister of Higher
Education Ignatius Chombo and Parliament Speaker Cyril Ndebele,
they explained the reasons for resisting the new policy as well
as offering possible solutions to the current problem. 
</P>
