<HEADLINE> APEC Financiers' Group to set up Clearing House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) Financiers' Group said today it is setting up
an information center which will serve as a clearing house of
information related to infrastructure finance.
</P>
<P>
Johnny Noe Ravalo, chairman of the APEC Financiers' Group, said
in an interview that the information center is vital in locating
investment opportunities elsewhere, particularly in APEC-member
nations.
</P>
<P>
"If you try to set up an internet workbase where all their
information are already available, the answer is just a click
away," Ravalo explained.
</P>
<P>
According to Ravalo, who is also director of the Bankers
Association of the Philippines, there are actually four major
areas tackled during the APEC Finance Ministers' Meeting last
weekend in Cebu City.
</P>
<P>
These include the private sector participation in
infrastructure finance, the freer flow of capital, financial
system in capital market development, and data dissemination.
</P>
<P>
Ravalo pointed out that infrastructure finance, information
center setup, access to equity and the development of bond market
fall under the private sector infrastructure finance which is
currently being given support by the Philippine government.
</P>
<P>
The participation of the APEC Financiers' Group was decided
during the 1994 APEC Finance Ministers' Meeting in Honolulu which
led to its formation later, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the group serves as an admission advisory body
created to address the needs of the market within the APEC region.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
