<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Changing Traditional Interment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEIHAI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- These days in Shandong Province,
rural folk are more likely to keep the memories, but not the
ashes, of their recently dead.
</P>
<P>
In Wendeng of the coastal city Weihai, relatives declined to
preserve the ashes of the dead in more than 1,000 cases last year,
28 percent of the total dead, according to officials with the
city's Civil Affairs Department.
</P>
<P>
Sun Defan, a farmer in Shaliu Village of Wendeng city, said
that it's better to take good care of the old and make them happy
when they are alive rather than to preserve their ashes after they
pass away.
</P>
<P>
When his parents died years ago, he had their remains cremated
but didn't take the ashes back.
</P>
<P>
More neighbors began to follow his example. Cremation started
in the village in the early 1960s and graves were smoothed into
farmland. Farmers gradually discarded traditional burials of the
dead. Instead they buried the ashes in mountain valleys, under
pine trees or kept them in the village's ashes hall, said Zhang
Baozhen, the elderly civil affairs director of the village.
</P>
<P>
Giving dinners or sending gifts on funeral and death
anniversary occasions became a heavy burden. Most farmers have
willingly abandoned the practice of keeping the ashes of the dead,
Zhang continued.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
