<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Bride Waiting 60 years for Husband </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Eighty-five-year-old Chen Ximei felt
heartbroken while standing on the warship that sank together with
her husband in the Yangtze River during a Japanese bombing attack
in 1938.
</P>
<P>
The cruiser, named "Chungshan" after Dr. Sun Yat-sen, the
forerunner of China's democratic revolution, was lifted out of
water in this January.
</P>
<P>
Chen sent her husband, Lin Yizi, to the cruiser, where he
served, in 1938. It was only 36 days after they got married. The
bride waited for 60 years, cleaning every day a suitcase and a
cabinet the bridegroom left behind, hoping that he would return
one day and see his beloved.
</P>
<P>
But she never knew for sure until this March that her husband
died in the sunken warship on October 24, 1938, in the battle to
guard the city of Wuhan. "I want to see the warship," the old
woman demanded when she was told of the truth.
</P>
<P>
On the Qingming festival, which fell on April 5, a tearful Chen
was brought on the cruiser, holding a grave-marker, a garland, and
offerings. She burned incense to and poured a glass of liquor for
the dead, murmuring long-constrained longings.
</P>
<P>
The faithful bride preserved three of her dresses. "Yizi (the
dead husband) said they suited me best, and I would not put them
on again until he was back."
</P>
<P>
But now she is determined to wear those dresses and go to see
her bridegroom in them.
</P>
<P>
"The martyrs on the cruiser will long live in our memory and we
will never forget the tragic history," said a Hong Kong
compatriot, who accompanied Chen to the warship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
