<HEADLINE> China Emphasising Developing Transportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- China will give priority to
transportation construction in the next few years and has
designated 35 key national projects in the field for 1997.
</P>
<P>
The projects are part of the central government's efforts to
improve China's basic industries, infrastructure, and investment
environment, according to an announcement on Tuesday by the State
Planning Commission (SPC).
</P>
<P>
The projects are: 15 in the railway sector, including the
Baoji-Chengdu double track project and the Southern Xinjiang
Railway project; 18 highway, and port and berth projects,
including the Beijing-Shenzhen Expressway, and Tianjin Port; and
two civil aviation projects, the Beijing Capital Airport Terminal,
and Haikou's Meilan Airport in Hainan Province.
</P>
<P>
China will build 40 large-scale airports during its Ninth Five
Year Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
The SPC called on ministries, local governments, and financial
institutions to provide support for these projects, especially
financial, and asked all departments to limit beginning any new
projects that may divert limited resources to purposes other than
these projects.  
</P>
