<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Develop Rare-Earth Processing Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai is to speed up its
rare-earth processing industries by furthering research of the
material's use in local industries.
</P>
<P>
China has 80 percent of the world's reserves in rare-earth
elements. In Shanghai, the country set up the first business to
separate 17 rare earth elements.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has 32 scientific research institutes and 15 colleges
and universities devoted to the study of the use of the material,
and nearly 100 industrial enterprises involved in development and
application of products made from rare-earth elements.
</P>
<P>
Hi-tech materials made from rare earth are widely used in
Shanghai in more than 10 industries, such as metallurgy,
instruments and meters, machinery, and electronics.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai leads the country in the development of luminous
materials made from rare earth, contributing 70 percent of the
country's total output of primary-colors phosphor powder. It also
aims at developing multi-color phosphor powder or other kinds for
large-screen color TVs and computers.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai produces about 12 miilion fluorescent lamps a year,
one-fifth of China's output.
</P>
<P>
In addition the city is expected to produce 250 tons of
permanent-magnet materials, and earn 420 million yuan in output
value from producing 300,000 electric motors based on such
materials annually by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
The city will give priority to increasing the use of rare earth
in the construction industry and in the manufacture of batteries
used in electric motor cars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
