<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Unveils Rules on Convertible Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- China has unveiled a set of
provisional rules on the management of convertible bonds, paving
the way for more enterprises to raise funds through floating such
bonds.
</P>
<P>
The rules, approved by the State Council and issued by the
Securities Committee under the State Council, are applicable to
the qualified listed companies and the designated key state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
As a qualification for issuing convertible bonds, a listed
company must have made a profit in the latest three years and have
an average net asset-profit ratio of above 10 percent during that
period. For those listed firms in the sectors of energy, raw
materials, and infrastructure, the net asset-profit ratio can be
lowered, but to no less than seven percent.
</P>
<P>
The rules also said that the firms' assets-liabilities ratio
must not be higher than 70 percent following a convertible bond
issue and the accumulated outstanding bond volume must not exceed
40 percent of their net asset value.
</P>
<P>
The funds raised through a bond issue must be used in line with
State industrial policies and the bond interest rate must not be
higher than that of the bank deposits of the same maturity, the
rules stipulate.
</P>
<P>
The value of each bond issue can not be less than 100 million
yuan and the bond terms should be no less than three years but no
more than five years, according to the rules.
</P>
<P>
The unlisted key state-owned enterprises must have their
financial books in the last three years audited and must have
clear and practical plans for restructuring and listing before
they are allowed to issue convertible bonds, the rules said,
adding that they must also be guaranteed by solvent guarantors.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of China Securities Regulatory Commission said that
at the current stage only a certain number of key state-owned
enterprises will be selected to issue convertible bonds on a trial
basis and no listed companies will be selected.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises will be selected from the 500 designated key
state-owned enterprises that have not been listed and the total
bond issue is planned at four billion yuan, he added.
</P>
<P>
Recommendations for a convertible bond issue are accepted
between today and May 10, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: No Headway in UF-Congress Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The first round of formal talks
between the Congress Party and the United Front (UF) to resolve
the 11-day-old political crisis due to the Congress' withdrawal of
support to the UF on March 30 made no headway here on Wednesday as
both sides stuck to their own stand.
</P>
<P>
While the Congress delegation remained adamant that the Deve
Gowda should give way to a Congress President Sitaram Kesri-led
coalition government, the UF delegation remained resolute that the
issue of the leadership of Mr. Gowda was "not negotiable".
</P>
<P>
The Congress delegation was of the view that it had given 10
months to the UF to rule the country and now it was for the UF to
reciprocate. The UF delegation reportedly told the Congress that
if there was any communication gap, the Front was prepared to
bridge it. The Congress did not favor the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
The deadlock is likely to continue unless either of the two
sides soften their stands when they meet here today to continue
their formal talks.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen after two and a half hour talks Wednesday
evening, one of the Congress negotiator J.Prasada said that "We
will come to an agreement." UF negotiator N. Chandrababu Naidu
also said that "We are hopeful of coming to an agreement."
</P>
<P>
Wednesday evening's formal talks were preceded by a great deal
of drama. In the morning, the core committee of the UF met at
Prime Minister Deve Gowda's residence on 7, Race Course Road here
and decided to send a formal letter to the Congress to invite its
representatives for a "formal discussion". After the Congress
accepted the invitation, both sides chose their team for the
talks.
</P>
<P>
After addressing a rally at his residence on Wednesday, Gowda
told newsmen that the UF steering committee had agreed to set up a
coordination committee with the Congress and hoped that the
leaders from the two sides would find an amicable solution to end
the impasse. He attributed "lack of communication",
"misunderstanding" and "misgivings" between the UF and the
Congress for the strained relations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Congress President Sitaram Kesri reportedly directed his team
to carry out negotiations with the UF team on the following five
issues: The question of UF leadership, sharing of power, budget
for 1997-98, pending court cases against politicians and others
and the general law and order and communal situation. In the
talks, the UF was reported to have offered the following four
proposals: Gowda be allowed to continue at least till the
Parliament session is over on May 9, the budget be passed in the
interest of the country on April 21, a monitoring committee be
formed to oversee government's functioning and Congress-UF
relations and the Congress will be formally invited to join the
government after the session.
</P>
<P>
No political party got a simple majority in the general
election held on April-May last year and therefore no political
party was capable to form a government at the Center. Among the
543 elected seats in the Lower House of Parliament, the 14-party
UF secured 188 including 11 supporters, while the Congress got 141
seats and the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), the biggest opposition
in the country, won 193 with its alliance. In order to prevent the
so-called "communal force" of BJP from coming to power, the
Congress, which could not come to power itself, decided to support
the UF and to rule the country from outside. After its withdrawal
of support, President S.D. Sharma asked the UF to show its
majority in the Parliament by April 11.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
