<HEADLINE> Chongqing Sets to Become Scientific Powerhouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing has the capability to
become a new scientific powerhouse in the underdeveloped central
and western regions, according to city officials.
</P>
<P>
A municipal government spokesman said today that the city in
southwest China has 399 scientific research institutes and
laboratories with 400,000 researchers, which will turn the hilly
region into a high-technology valley in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Researchers are engaged in 20 industries including electronics,
meters, telecommunications, metallurgy, machinery and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The city, with a population of 30 million, was approved last
month as the fourth municipality directly under the central
government after Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
The central government hopes that the city will solve
resettlement problem caused by the Three Gorges Reservoir on the
Yangtze River, help develop the poorest western regions, and
improve state enterprises and and expand the rural economy.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the city is planning to improve its
image as a regional industrial center, and develop into an
inland scientific powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chongqing has 27 universities and colleges, and
has been carrying out a program to revive the city by using
science since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Many of the city's military plants are converting their
technology for civilian purposes, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the Second World War, Chongqing was appointed as the
"interim capital" of China, when a great number of major
enterprises and research institutes were evacuated to the area.
</P>
<P>
"We are preparing to import more foreign expertise before the
year 2000," the spokesman said. The city now has scientific
cooperations with 16 countries and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
