<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rating Downgrade May Cost Thailand More Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will have to
do more in raising investors' confidence after the U.S.-based
Moody's investors service recently downgraded its foreign currency
rating for all bonds and bank deposits of Thailand from A2 to A3.
</P>
<P>
The downgrade by the U.S. credit rating agency apparently will
affect the Thai government's planned issuance of 500 million U.S.
dollar Yankee bonds, which is aimed at testing investors'
confidence in the country.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that the timing of Moody's downgrade
could not have been so worse, as it was announced just before Thai
Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Amnuay Virawan was to
sit down with investors to price the Yankee bond issue in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Moody's said that the downgrade reflected an incremental
deterioration in Thailand's creditworthiness.
</P>
<P>
The rate agency cited four factors contributing to its
downgrade, a buildup of short-term debt, a structural problem in
Thailand's labor-intensive export industries, limitations on the
Thai government macro-economic policies, and the current crisis in
Thailand's financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Despite the downgrade, however, Moody's indicated that
Thailand's fundamentals remained strong and foreign direct
investment remained steady due to its favorable geological
location and liberal trade and investment policies.
</P>
<P>
It also said that Thailand's foreign exchange reserves (more
than 39 billion dollars) are strong enough to handle external debt
shocks.
</P>
<P>
Moody's downgrade this time seemed having less impact on the
Thai financial sector than that it made last year. The stock
exchange of Thailand (SET) index Wednesday dropped slightly 2.73
points to close at 712.63.
</P>
<P>
Thai central bank officials noted that Moody's downgrade
ignored the Thai government's measures and ongoing efforts to
address economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Moody's chose to analyze the economic from a static
perspective, not a dynamic one, they added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macedonia Hails Annan's Call on Halting Cut in U.N. Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Macedonia has welcomed United
Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan's proposal to suspend a
planned reduction of the U.N. forces in the country.
</P>
<P>
A defense ministry spokesman highly praised Annan's proposal on
Wednesday, noting that the U.N. Protective Deployment Force
(UNPREDEP) is needed in the former Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
The risks of potential crises and their escalation were still
there in the Balkan region, as demonstrated by the Bosnian war,
the Kosovo issue and the recent unrest in Albania, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary to keep the U.N. peacekeeping force in
Macedonia before regional disputes are resolved, the spokesman was
quoted as saying by reports from the country's capital of Skoplje.
</P>
<P>
Annan recommended suspending UNPREDEP's downsizing in a letter
to the president of the U.N. Security Council on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Recent developments in Albania and the resulting situation of
lawlessness and banditry in certain parts of that country have
demonstrated that stability in the Balkan region remains extremely
fragile," the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
Although there was "no imminent danger of the problems in
Albania spilling over to the former Yugoslav Republic of
Macedonia, the current crisis is a source of great anxiety in that
country," he added.
</P>
<P>
Grouping together 500 Nordic troops, 500 U.S. soldiers, 50
Indonesian army engineers, 35 military observers and 26 police
monitors, the UNPREDEP was sent to Macedonia in late 1992 to deter
spread of violence from other parts of the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council last November renewed the UNPREDEP
mandate for six months until May 31, 1997, but with a phased
reduction of 300 troops to be completed by April 30.
</P>
<P>
The dismantling of the UNPREDEP observation posts along the
borders with Yugoslavia at the end of March had brought criticism
from Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Macedonian Foreign Minister Ljubomir Frckovski, in a letter
then, asked the United Nations to suspend the reduction of the
force after underlining the seriousness of the regional
situation. 
</P>
