<HEADLINE> Nepal's Ruling Party Chief Calls Coalition Unnatural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's major ruling party
chief has described the present ruling coalition as "unnatural"
and predicted it would not last long.
</P>
<P>
The unnatural coalition between the Communist Party of Nepal
(United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML) and Prime Minister Lokendra
Bahadur Chand's National Democratic Party (RPP) is soon coming to
its end, CPN-UML President Man Mohan Adhikari said Wednesday at a
talk program here.
</P>
<P>
Adhikari, whose party formed a government with the RPP last
month after a former coalition government between the Nepali
Congress (NC) party and the RPP lost a vote of confidence in
parliament, said that the present coalition would fall due to the
RPP's treachery.
</P>
<P>
RPP leader Chand is leading the present government after he
successfully brought down the NC-led government by withdrawing one
RPP faction's support.
</P>
<P>
The RPP party, formed in 1990 after the country abolished the
partyless Panchayat legislature and introduced the multi-party
parliamentary system, mainly comprise former Panchayat
legislators.
</P>
<P>
Adhikari also said Wednesday that the CPN-UML and the NC, the
two biggest parties which jointly ushered in the parliamentary
democracy through the 1990 Popular Movement, need urgently to
reach some kind of understanding on the political situation in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The RPP party, with its 19 MPs in the lower house of
parliament, has become a key player on Nepal's political arena as
none the CPN-UML and the NC has majority in the 205-seat house.
</P>
</TEXT>
