<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Doctors on Strike for Salary Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 10 (Xinhua) -- About 1,700 doctors attached to
Sri Lanka's government hospitals went on a 24 hour token strike
from 8 a.m. today in protest against the failure of the government
to resolve their salary anomalies problem with the given one month
period.
</P>
<P>
However, the Government Medical Officers Union (GMOA) said they
would maintain emergency services in every hospital and doctors in
hospitals in the North and East where the ethnic war is on will
work as usual, according to informed sources here.
</P>
<P>
The GMOA which struck on March 5 for the same reason called it
off after the government appointed a Cabinet Sub Committee of
three ministers to find a solution to their grievances within a
month.
</P>
<P>
The GMOA had made submissions to the committee which had
presented an agreeable report in time to President Chandrika
Kumaratunga, but the government had neither published the report
nor acted on it as another report had been submitted by a Treasury
official, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources pointed out that the token strike is being staged
because five months of negotiations had been fruitless.  
