<HEADLINE> German Diaries of Nanjing Massacre to Appear in Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The eight-volume diary of German
John Rabe, cataloguing Japanese atrocities during the massacre in
Nanjing in World War Two, will be available in Chinese by October.
</P>
<P>
The Nanjing People's Printing House has signed a copyright deal
with Germany's Stuttgart Printing House to publish the diaries in
Chinese, Cai Yuhua, director of the Chinese publisher said today.
</P>
<P>
He said his company would have the Chinese version out in six
months, either by commissioning the translation itself, or
reselling the copyright, Cai said.
</P>
<P>
John Rabe's 2400-page diary and photos describe in detail the
horrors committed by Japanese soldiers during their massacre of an
estimated 300,000 Chinese people in Nanjing in 1937.
</P>
<P>
He kept the diaries and took photographs while working in
Nanjing in the 1930s as the chief representative of German
engineering giant Siemens. But they were only made public by his
grand-daughter Ursula Reinhardt in December last year on the 59th
anniversary of the siege of Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
Cai and a delegation from the Nanjing People's Printing House
also visited Ursula Reinhardt. She is due to visit Nanjing at the
invitation of Nanjing City Government later this year on the 60th
anniversary of the Nanjing Massacre. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
