<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Forum Discusses Folklore Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 10 (Xinhua) -- A three-day world forum on the
protection of folklore is being held in Phuket, southern Thailand.
</P>
<P>
About 120 participants from dozens of countries or regions are
attending the forum, which began on Wednesday and is organized by
the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO) and the World Intellectual Property
Organization (WIPO).
</P>
<P>
Forum organizers hope to sort out how governments can agree on
a definition of folklore and folk art and the scope of their
protection.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time for countries to reopen negotiations on a
folklore protection agreement.
</P>
<P>
Mihaly Ficsor, assistant director general of the Geneva-based
WIPO, admitted that "it is possible but not easy" to include the
protection of folklore in the existing multilateral agreements of
the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Most countries in the world today do not have protection rights
for folklore and folk art, and experts cannot even agree on a
definition of folklore. They have difficulty identifying which
heritage belongs exclusively to which country. This is
particularly the case when it comes to countries in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mihaly Ficsor agreed that folklore and folk art should be
legally governed by international regulation, in a fashion similar
to other types of intellectual property rights. Otherwise, it
might be distorted by modern technology and commercial use.
</P>
<P>
Prof Kamal Puri of Australia said at the meeting that the
widespread use of aboriginal art for commercial purposes was
exploitation of the native people's heritage. In the case of some
contemporary designs, the exploitation takes place without even
the permission of the original artists.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, aboriginal designs on items such as towels,
T-shirts, shorts, sarongs, table cloths and carpets are easily
available to tourists.
</P>
<P>
Some participants said they hoped that the true purpose should
not be to put a price on the cultural heritage of the world,
rather it should be to ensure that heritage is preserved in its
original form, maintained and passed on to succeeding generations.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Debt Rises Sharply in Czech Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Sluggish economic growth pushed up
the foreign debt of the Czech Republic to a total of 20.7 billion
U.S. dollars in 1996, up 20 percent against the previous year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, according to latest statistics released by the
Czech State Bank, the central European nation's per capita foreign
debt rose to 2,000 dollars in 1996 from 822 dollars in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Once one of the least indebted nations in the region and entire
Europe, the Czech Republic saw the foreign debt edging dangerously
toward 40 percent of the country's gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
It registered a total of 8.5 billion dollars in foreign debt in
1993, and 16.5 billion dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Of last year's external debt, considered alarming by
international standards, 11 billion dollars, or a hike by one
third over 1995, were owed to foreign commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Besides slow economic growth, analysts here also blamed a
fiscal deficit, lower foreign reserves and a foreign trade deficit
of about 5.725 billion dollars for the year's debt increase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
