<HEADLINE> Thailand, U.S. to Stage Joint Military Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and the United States
will hold their annual military exercises, codenamed "Cobra Gold
'97," in Thailand during April 17-May 29, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The kickoff ceremony of the war games, which will involve about
10,000 military personnel each from Thailand and the U.S., will be
held in Phitsanulok province and co-chaired by Thai Supreme
Commander Gen. Mongkol Ampornpisit and the U.S. ambassador to
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The exercises will include a landing exercise scheduled for May
20 at Sattahip in Rayong province, and a joint combat
demonstration in Sukhothai province scheduled for May 23.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. will send 90 aircraft, including 42 F-18 jets, three
C-130s, and reconnaissance aircraft, and nine warships, including
the aircraft carrier "Independence," to the events.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will send 19 warships and 29 aircraft to join the
games.
</P>
<P>
The exercises will be jointly directed by Thai Third Army
Region deputy commander Maj. Gen. Sommai Wichaporn and Rear
Admiral Joseph S. Mobley, commander of the U.S. Pacific Command.
