<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Senate Passes Anti-Drug Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Senate Wednesday
adopted an anti-drug bill empowering the proposed force to
confiscate the property of the convicted drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
The Anti Narcotics Force Act, 1997, was moved by Federal
Minister for Interior Chaudhry Shujat Hussain suggesting to
establish a force to check the manufacture and smuggling of
narcotics inside as well as outside the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that there was a need for the constitution of the force
to investigate the preparation, production, manufacture and
smuggling of narcotics.
</P>
<P>
After the enactment of the law, the Pakistan Narcotics Control
Board constituted in 1973 and the Anti-Narcotics task force set up
in 1994 under an ordinance, stand merged.
</P>
<P>
The members of the force enjoy the right to trace the assets of
a person about whom there is a reasonable suspicion that the
assets were acquired through illicit involvement in narcotics.
</P>
<P>
The force could provide assistance and advice to other
enforcement agencies on narcotics and collect information from the
national and international enforcement agencies about illicit
narcotics traffic and traffickers.
</P>
<P>
It could also maintain liaison with all national or
international or narcotics authorities, organizations, bodies,
associations and societies and represent Pakistan in conferences,
seminars and workshops arranged by such organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
