<HEADLINE> China's Shougang Company to Build New Plant in Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese-funded Shougang Iron
Company (Peru) will invest 137 million U.S. dollars in the
construction of an iron pellet plant in Peru, local press reports
said today.
</P>
<P>
The new plant will have the capacity to produce 3 million tons
of iron pellets a year, reports quoted company president Wang
Jinrui as saying.
</P>
<P>
A feasibility study has already been made and the company is
evaluating proposals from U.S., Japanese, and Spanish consortiums
for the construction of the plant.
</P>
<P>
The company is also in contact with some French and Spanish
energy consortiums for the building of a 300 megawatt power plant
to back the iron pellet plant.
</P>
<P>
Shougang Iron (Peru) was set up in 1992 after Shougang, the
largest iron and steel company in China, purchased the Peruvian
Iron Company for 120 million dollars together with its
41-million-dollar debt. 
