<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua to Spend 7 Million Dollars to Clear Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Nicaragua will spend 7 million
U.S. dollars provided by Denmark, Germany, Sweden, United States
and the European Union to clear land mines in its border areas, a
Nicaraguan officer said today.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Ugarte, chief of the section of military engineers of
the Army Operations and Programs Division, said there are about
90,000 anti-tank and anti-personnel mines in Nicaragua, 55,000 of
which on the northern border zone.
</P>
<P>
Ugarte acknowledged that Nicaraguan army has set up a technical
and professional unit of sappers consisting of 300 men in 11
platoons to deactivate and destroy these mines buried in the past
decade during the country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
The officer said these servicemen are now working in three key
areas: the northern border, the southern border and around
high-voltage power transmission line pylons.
</P>
<P>
Land mines have claimed lives of 456 civilian farmers and 87
army servicemen so far. In addition, 13 soldiers were killed and
10 others injured during mine clearing operations.
</P>
<P>
To prevent further bloodshed, the army has launched a
nationwide publicity and educational campaign directed to farmers,
and posted signs in mine fields warning people to stay out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
