<HEADLINE> Launch of Thaicom 3 Satellite Put Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The launch of the Thaicom 3
satellite, originally set for Saturday, has been postponed by a
week, according to Nongluck Pinainitisart, vice-president of
Shinawatra Satellite Plc today.
</P>
<P>
Arianespace of France, the satellite's launcher, has informed
Shinawatra of a week's delay while the adaptor connecting the
satellite and the launcher was being adjusted.
</P>
<P>
The satellite arrived at the launching pad in French Guiana in
mid-March.
</P>
<P>
After the launch, the satellite will go into a controlled orbit
for tests, a process likely to take two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The delay will not have any impact on customers as services
will start in June as scheduled, Nongluck said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, talks would continue on avoiding interference with
the footprint of a Russian satellite, said Nongluck.
</P>
<P>
Shinawatra is trying to relocate the transponders of Thaicom 3
which has overlapping footprint as the Russian craft.  
</P>
</TEXT>
