<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinkel: EMU, Single Currency Course Won't Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The timetable for launching
European Monetary Union (EMU) and the single currency remains on
schedule for January 1, 1999, German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
said today during a 24-hour visit to Portugal.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said Germany is working hard to meet the EMU criteria
set out in the European Union's Maastricht Treaty, but he admitted
some problems still exist.
</P>
<P>
He referred to the postwar record high unemployment of 4.67
million, or 12.2 percent, in February and doubts over the speed at
which the German economy will expand in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The Maastricht Treaty sets out a list of convergence criteria
on budget deficits, debt, inflation, interest rates and exchange
rates, which EU member states must meet before they can join the
single currency.
</P>
<P>
But Germany, one of the main players in the currency, is having
trouble meeting some of the criteria, notably the budget deficit
conditions.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after talks with his Portuguese
counterpart Jaime Gama, Kinkel said EMU will not exist without the
participation of Germany and France.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that small EU economies like Portugal would be
among the first wave of countries joining the single currency, the
Euro.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, EU finance ministers and central bankers held an
informal meeting in the Netherlands, agreeing that the decision on
which countries join the single currency would be made in late
April or early May.
</P>
<P>
They also endorsed plans to penalize countries running budget
deficit above the regulated three percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Before March 1, 1998, each EU member state is required to
provide the European Commission with final information on the
country's 1997 budget performance.
</P>
<P>
The Commission and the European Monetary Institute, the
forerunner of the future European Central Bank, will then have
about two weeks to come up with their convergence reports.
</P>
<P>
After the evaluation, there will be a six-week consultation
period with the European Parliament, before a summit of EU leaders
meets to adopt the list of countries due to join the Euro on
January 1, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
