<HEADLINE> Central America Proposes Agenda for Summit With Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The governments of five Central
American countries have put forward an initial agenda for the
coming summit between the five countries' presidents and
U.S. President Bill Clinton, Costa Rican Foreign Ministry said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The agenda was submitted to the U.S. State Department on
Tuesday by the ambassadors of Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala,
Honduras and Nicaragua in Washington. The details of the proposal
were not made public.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here believed that the agenda would include
a free trade agreement between Central America and the United
States, migration, anti-narcotic cooperation and initiatives for
improving democracy and the environment in the isthmus.
</P>
<P>
Central American foreign ministers met last week with U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in Washington for an initial
exchange of points of view about the summit agenda.
</P>
<P>
The Central American countries want to finalize in an agreement
the preferential tariff treatments which would guarantee the
access of Central American goods to the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
They believe that the North American Free Trade Agreement,
signed by the United States, Canada and Mexico in August 1992,
made Mexico attractive to foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
The agreement has enabled Mexico to absorb foreign capitals
which would have otherwise been invested in Central America, they
complained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
