<HEADLINE> Philippine Garments Exports Continue Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Export receipts from the
Philippines' garments sector continued to inch up, reaching 692.1
million U.S. dollars during the first three months of this year,
the local newspaper Business Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Documents from the Garments and Textile Export Board showed
total garment exports grew 3.3 percent from 669.9 million US
dollars posted during the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Quota countries led by the U.S. recorded an average 2.67
percent increase in shipments amounting to 528.9 million US
dollars, accounting for 76.4 percent of the total garments
exports.
</P>
<P>
Shipments to the U.S. showed a significant 5.3 percent rise to
418.97 million U.S. dollars from 397.8 million U.S. dollars last
year.
</P>
<P>
Garment exports to Canada also rose 2.75 percent to reach 13.9
million U.S. dollars, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But garment exports to the European Union, which is composed of
quota countries, dropped slightly to 96 million U.S. dollars from
103.8 million U.S. dollars the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Shipments to non-quota countries, on the other hand, continued
to outpace those bound for quota countries with 5.4 percent growth
amounting to 163.2 million U.S. dollars compared with 154 million
U.S. dollars the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Japan continued to lead non-quota countries with 48.9 million
U.S. dollar worth of garment exports followed by the United Arab
Emirates with 18.3 million U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
