<HEADLINE> Reinforced Poverty Relief Drive in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Gansu Province
is trying every means possible this year to solve the food and
clothing problem for another one million poverty-stricken people.
</P>
<P>
According to a local source, 1.22 million people in the
province rose out of poverty last year, and the relief drive has
been reinforced this year by ten major efforts in farmland
construction, pillar industries, local scientific, educational and
health development, and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government appropriated 369 million yuan this
year for the purpose, an increase of 100 million yuan over the
1996 figure.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Provincial Agricultural Development Bank
provided 480 million in loans, an increase of nearly 200 million
yuan over last year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of last year, there were still
over three million people living below the poverty line in the
province, mainly in arid mountainous areas and in ethnic minority
areas.
</P>
<P>
In addition to these means of helping the local people, other
effective measures such as providing labor services to other parts
of the country and resettling poverty-stricken people are being
taken. Local officials expect that 1.5 million laborers will be
offered job opportunities outside the province this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
