<HEADLINE> Japan's Consul-General Optimistic About HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese Consul-General in
Hong Kong, Hideaki Ueda, said he firmly believes that it is up to
the people of Hong Kong to use their accumulated experience to
achieve the successful implementation of the Basic Law into
meaningful everyday administration.
</P>
<P>
He told the press recently that 1997 marks the end of the 19th
century European colonization of Asia and it is a massively
historic event.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Since Japan has such a big stake in Hong Kong's
future, we are ready to support a Hong Kong governed by Hong Kong
people, an autonomous Hong Kong backed up by the principle of "One
Country, Two Systems."
</P>
<P>
He said Japan was the second biggest exporter to Hong Kong, the
fourth largest recipient of Hong Kong's domestic exports, and the
third largest recipient of its re-exports.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,000 Japanese businesses now operate in Hong Kong, and
787 Japanese firms are currently listed as members of the Japanese
Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-eight Japanese banks now have offices here, he said.
</P>
<P>
On Sino-Japanese relations, Hideaki Ueda said 1997 marks the
25th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic ties between
Japan and China.
</P>
<P>
He said, "On the whole, we have seen a positive trend of
enhancement of relations between our two nations."
</P>
<P>
He said that since the post-1997 status of the
Consulate-General of Japan in Hong Kong was secured, it will
continue to function after Hong Kong's handover.
</P>
<P>
He said he was confident that Hong Kong can also play an
important role in furthering Sino-Japanese relations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
