<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amended Criminal Law to Punish Polluters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The newly amended criminal law,
which is scheduled to take effect on October 1, will hold
environmental polluters and those who damage natural environment
and resources responsible for their actions, according to today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Bie Tao, an official with the National Environmental Protection
Agency (Nepa), said implementation of the Criminal Law would help
control the discharge and import of hazardous wastes.
</P>
<P>
The new Criminal Law, which was amended and passed by the
session of National People's Congress last month, includes a
special article on punishing -- with years of imprisonment and
fines -- those work units and people who import waste for dumping,
storage or disposal.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several years, nearly 20 cases of importing
hazardous solid wastes from abroad have taken place in China.
</P>
<P>
Some developed countries are using developing countries,
including China, as dumping sites for solid waste that is harmful
to the environment and human health, Bie said.
</P>
<P>
With the new Criminal Law, importers of harmful wastes would be
punished for jeopardizing the environment, he said.
</P>
<P>
William Ping Chen, who was found guilty of importing 238 tons
of household waste from the US, was sentenced to ten years in
prison and fined 500,000 yuan (60,240 US dollars) for smuggling in
December of last year.
</P>
<P>
Under the new Criminal Law, he would be punished for seriously
jeopardizing the country's environment, according to Bie.
</P>
<P>
The 338th article of the Criminal Law stipulates that the
discharge, dumping and disposal of harmful wastes that are
radioactive or contain infectious elements, pathogens or toxic
substances, and other dangerous wastes that result in serious
damage to public and private property or human health, should be
sentenced to years of imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Personnel in environmental protection departments who, through
dereliction of duty, allow serious pollution accidents to occur,
can also be put into prison, according to the law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
