<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People In Shanghai Buying More Insurance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Branch of PICC Life
has written 500 million yuan worth of policies locally in the
first two months of this year, as the people of Shanghai flock to
insurance companies to look after their social well-being.
</P>
<P>
The People's Insurance Company of China (PICC) is the country's
largest insurer and had a monopoly on China's insurance market
before it was split up last year.
</P>
<P>
"More Chinese people are turning to insurance companies, as the
social welfare system under the planned economy disappears and a
new one hasn't yet taken shaped," insurance experts say.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises and government offices in China used to
cover medical bills of their staff, provide them with
housing, and pensions when they retired.
</P>
<P>
"But such privileges are gone, and I have to buy commercial
pension insurance for the years when I cannot work, and it gives
me a sense of safety," explained one middle-aged worker.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, on average about 60,000 to 70,000
people bought life insurance policies from PICC Life's Shanghai
branch in each of the past three months.
</P>
<P>
The figure is about double that of last year, said Zhao
Qinfang, sales manager of the Shanghai Branch. Shanghai people are
riding the crest of a life insurance wave in China's largest
financial and trade city, she said.
</P>
<P>
The company's premium earnings for the first two months of the
year equal about half last year's total, she noted. "Some families
even bought a dozen different policies on their first visit to my
company," she added.
</P>
<P>
China is seen as having a burgeoning insurance market, which is
expected to see sales of from 200 to 250 billion yuan a year by
the year 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
