<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (13-14) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (13-14)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Do the various departments of the central government
hold any direct authority over related departments of the Hong
Kong SAR?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Since Hong Kong will enjoy a high degree of autonomy
after 1997 in accordance with the policy of "one country, two
systems," there will be no subordinate relationship between the
various departments of the central authorities and their
counterparts in the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the Ministry of Public Security will not exercise
any leadership over the police department of the Hong Kong SAR,
nor will the General Administration of Customs have any authority
over the customs of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
No central and local government departments may interfere in
affairs administered by the Hong Kong SAR on its own in accordance
with provisions of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Public servants of the Hong Kong SAR at various levels are
accountable only to the government of the SAR, while the chief
executive is accountable to the central government and the Hong
Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
Nongovernmental organizations in the fields of education,
science and technology, culture and sports and religious
organizations in the Hong Kong SAR and their counterparts in the
mainland will follow the principle of no subordination,
non-interference and mutual respect in the handling of their
relations.
</P>
<P>
Question: Who will give the approval if central government
departments and provinces, autonomous regions and
centrally-administered municipalities want to set up offices in
Hong Kong after 1997? Should such offices abide by laws of the
Hong Kong SAR?
</P>
<P>
Answer: The Basic Law stipulates that, if there is a need for
departments of the central government, or for provinces,
autonomous regions and centrally-administered municipalities to
set up offices in the Hong Kong SAR, they must obtain the prior
consent of the government of the Hong Kong SAR and approval of the
central government.
</P>
<P>
That is to say, no departments in the mainland may set up
offices in Hong Kong and send personnel there without the consent
of the Hong Kong SAR government and the approval of the central
government.
</P>
<P>
Strict approval procedures are required to send people to Hong
Kong, and the number of such people is limited. All such offices
in Hong Kong and their staff must abide by laws of the Hong Kong
SAR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
