<HEADLINE> Federal Agencies to Hire Welfare Recipients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Welfare recipients in the
United States will be offered work in federal offices, including
the Office of the President, under plans being drafted by
President Bill Clinton's Cabinet secretaries.
</P>
<P>
The president was expected to summon his Cabinet to the White
House on Thursday to review those plans.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Ann Lewis said Wednesday that the
president's executive office, one of the government's smallest
sectors, with 1,500 employees, would recruit and hire its share
from the welfare rolls as part of Clinton's drive to find jobs for
2 million welfare recipients over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore is overseeing the effort.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to ease the blow of welfare legislation he signed into
law last year, which imposed a lifetime benefits' limit of five
years for families on welfare, Clinton has pushed the private
sector, nonprofit groups and churches to find room on their
payrolls for welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
With 1.9 million people on its payroll and 58,000 hired last
year alone, the federal government is the nation's largest
employer.
</P>
<P>
In his weekly radio broadcast last month, Clinton gave agencies
30 days to develop recruitment and hiring plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
