<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Culture Spending Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- As the standard of living
improves, cultural spending by Beijing citizens has increased in
recent years, municipal statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Cultural consumption mainly includes entertainment, education,
books, papers, magazines, sightseeing, and going to cinemas and
theaters.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, average per-capita cultural spending was 699 yuan, an
increase of 37 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Per-capita spending on education showed the sharpest increase,
at 276 yuan, up 36 percent from the previous year, followed by
books, papers and magazines, up 27 percent to 69 yuan.
</P>
<P>
In third place was spending on large-screen TVs, VCDs, cameras,
computers, and other big-ticket items.
</P>
<P>
On average, there are 119 color TV sets, 58 VCRs, and 2 pianos
for every 100 urban households in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Money spent on going to cinemas, art exhibitions, and various
sports matches rose sharply. Average per capita spending on
entertainment hit 78.5 yuan, up 32 percent from the previous
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
