<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Chinese Province Vows to Eradicate Poverty in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 10 (Xinhua) -- The underdeveloped province of
Qinghai on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau has vowed to eliminate
poverty for 676,600 farmers before the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
A local senior official of the provincial government says that
the province plans to launch three major poverty-relief projects
in "a historic leap" of poverty eradication.
</P>
<P>
Qinghai plans to help poor farmers migrate from regions with
harsh natural conditions to the Qaidam Basin, where they can
create an oasis and make a better living.
</P>
<P>
It will spend two billion yuan over the next five years
supporting resettlement of 100,000 farmers, allowing them to
reclaim about 66,000 hectares of land and build seven reservoirs
and other supporting water conservancy projects.
</P>
<P>
In the southern part of the province, an area frequently hit by
natural disasters, the province will spend 720 million yuan on
building barns and cultivating grassland. Each household is to
have about 20 to 25 hectares of fenced grassland and barns of 60
square meters.
</P>
<P>
For poor people in the arid mountainous areas in the eastern
part of the province, the local government will concentrate
resources on capital construction and infrastructure to allow
residents to earn more from farming. The region's targets are
per-capita grain consumption of 400 kg and a net income of 500
yuan a year by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Local sources say that efforts to eradicate poverty in the past
several years have already paid off, with the number of poor in
the province dropping from 1.19 million in 1993 to 676,000 in
1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970410.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chretien Criticizes U.S. for U.N. Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Canadian Prime
Minister Jean Chretien today criticized the United States for
failing to pay the debt of more than one billion U.S. dollars to
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the National Press Club, Chretien said, "It's
inappropriate and it's wrong for the one who has the biggest debt
to use it to get its way."
</P>
<P>
He would like the U.N. headquarters, which are in New York, to
move to Montreal if it is agreed to.
</P>
<P>
"It's a big business, the city gets a good return and I would
be happy to take the United Nations in Montreal tomorrow," he told
reporters in laughter.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has promised to pay the due to the
U.N. but Chairman Jesse Helms of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee wants the organization to make reforms in accordance
with "benchmarks" he set for it before the due is paid.
</P>
<P>
Chretien said that the U.S. debt to the U.N. has seriously
undermined the organization's peacekeeping capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Chretien, who arrived here Monday on his first state visit to
the U.S., is expected to leave tonight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
