<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts Planned to Promote Race Relation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton is
expected to make efforts to improve race relations, the White
House said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Among the ideas being considered are a White House conference
on bigotry and discrimination and a commission to promote national
dialogue on racial concerns.
</P>
<P>
"He is analyzing different options, different scenarios. He's
working on getting it exactly right," said Rahm Emanuel, senior
adviser to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The conference is being pushed by civil rights activists who
have urged Clinton to act to stem an increase in hate crimes and
hateful rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
A White House task force is reportedly examining how previous
presidents have dealt with race matters.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said Clinton plans to make
"a fairly major address" on race relations as soon as he "has a
more structured sense of how he wants to pursue it."
</P>
<P>
"It's very much on his mind," McCurry said. "He continues to
see evidence of unfinished business when it comes to creating a
society in which Americans appreciate the diversity that is one of
the remarkable features of this country."
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Clinton plans to "acknowledge the pain that
has existed in the past because of evidence of prejudice and
hostility towards the races," McCurry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
