<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Plans to Evacuate Staff From Kinshasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations decided
on Wednesday to begin evacuating U.N. staff from Kinshasa, capital
of Zairea within the next 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
"In light of the deterioration of the security situation
there, the U.N. has taken the decision to reduce the size of its
presence there in the city," spokesman Juan-Carlos Brandt told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"There is talk that some (private) donor agencies and some
people in the humanitarian community are planning for an
evacuation of the city," he added, but gave no figures on the
size of the U.N. mission.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken after fierce clashes erupted in the
Zairian capital between soldiers and thousands of supporters of
ousted Prime Minister Etienne Tshisekedi.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers then seized Tshisekedi, who was appointed a week ago,
and drove him off in a vehicle. At the same time, rebels were
reported to have broken past Zairian troops and entered the
country's second-largest city, Lubumbashi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
