<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Hits New Highs Against yen, mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar hit a new high
against the yen for more than four years and a three-year high
against the mark in New York Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It was the dollar's fourth straight day of solid gains
propelled by the potentials of rising U.S. interest rates and lack
of central-bank concern over the dollar's strength.
</P>
<P>
The dollar hit an intraday high of 126.93 yen, the strongest
since August 1992, before settling at 126.77 yen, up from 126.52
yen Tuesday and up 3.4 percent since last Friday when the rally
began.
</P>
<P>
Against the mark the dollar reached an intraday high of 1.7272
marks, the strongest since March 1994, before settling at 1.7245
marks, up from 1.7143 Tuesday and up 2.3 percent since last
Friday. The pound cost 1.6194 U.S. dollars, down from 1.6260 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Without official warnings from Japan over the yen's decline,
traders dollar buying spree started early in Asian dealings.
Comments from senior Japanese monetary aides have suggested they
aren't overly concerned.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York compared with Tuesday:
1.4780 Swiss francs, up from 1.4735; 5.8020 French francs, up from
5.7660; 1,700.00 Italian lira, up from 1,688.50; 1.3898 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.3882. 
</P>
</TEXT>
