<HEADLINE> Countries Pledge Better Forest Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Wide Fund for
Nature called here today for greater efforts throughout the world
for a better protection of forests.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in the headquarters of the United
Nations, WWF gave out the names of 16 countries who have responded
to WWF's call to halt forest destruction and made a pledge to
conserve their forests. It also called on government
representatives attending the fifth meeting of the Commission on
Sustainable Development (CSD) to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
WWF set a protected areas target -- the establishment of an
ecologically representative network of protected areas covering a
minimum of 10 percent of each forest type. By the year 2000, a
range of socially and ecologically appropriate models should be
demonstrated, said Francis Sullivan, director of WWF Forests for
Life Campaign.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, a minimum of 10 percent of each forest
type should be permanently and properly protected from clearance
and degradation.
</P>
<P>
The 16 countries who have pledged to support WWF's target
include: Argentina, Australia, Canada, Chile, New Zealand, Romania
and Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
Recent research shows that over half of the world's forests
have already disappeared, and that 94 percent of the remaining
forests are unprotected. Forests are now under more acute pressure
than at any other time in history and continue to decline at an
alarming rate. Since the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro in 1992,
the annual rate of deforestation in the Brazilian Amazon alone has
increased by 34 percent, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
Kofi Annan, the United National Secretary General, said in a
special message to WWF that a target of placing 10 percent of the
world's forests under some form of legal protection needs to be
seen in a larger context.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
