<HEADLINE> U.S. Presses Mobutu to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Reports about U.S. trying to
press Zaire's President Mobutu Sese Seko to resign and go into
exile was confirmed on Wednesday when the White House believed he
"is not sufficient to lead Zaire into the next chapter of its
history."
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post on Wednesday quoted anonymous officials as
saying that the U.S. message of pressing Mobutu to go down has
been conveyed to the Zairian President in recent weeks by various
African leaders including King Hassan of Morocco.
</P>
<P>
At a White House briefing, White House spokesman Mike McCurry
told reporters: "Mobutuism is about to become a creature of
history, because the support for President Mobutu is not
sufficient to lead Zaire into the next chapter of its history."
</P>
<P>
A civil war erupted last October in eastern Zaire which soon
spread westward and rebel forces, led by Laurent Kabila, have now
controlled nearly half of the country. And on Wednesday, they
captured the second largest city of Lubumbashi, the capital of
Shaba Province. Now they are marching towards the capital of
Kinshasa after ceasefire talks between the Zairian government and
the rebels broke down this week.
</P>
<P>
McCurry declined to say whether the United States was actively
involved in finding an exile home for Mobutu, saying: "There has
to be... some arrangements made for a transitional process that
leads to a newly elected government."
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post said the United States has already made
clear it does not want him here. And the attitudes of France,
Belgium and Switzerland, where Mobutu has many properties and his
bank accounts, remain unclear.
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. analysts suggested a parallel between Mobutu's
quandary and that of the Shah of Iran, who had considerable
difficulty finding a country willing to take him in after he was
toppled in 1979.
</P>
<P>
"It's the story of the Shah all over again," said a source
close to the Mobutu family.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post said: "After more than two decades of
counting on Mobutu for the execution of U.S. covert and other
policies in Africa,... the United States began ... to move away
from him. By 1994, all U.S. military and economic assistance was
cut off, and restrictions were placed on visas for him to come
here because of his refusal to cooperate with American efforts to
establish a multiparty democracy in Zaire." 
</P>
</TEXT>
