<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: COMESA Strives for Regional Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Facing fierce competition in the
global economy and global trend of establishment of regional
economic blocs, the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA) has been promoting inter-regional trade and economic
integration.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA secretariat in a communique last week disclosed
that internal trade among its members jumped from 834 million
U.S. Dollars in 1985 to 1,700 million Dollars in 1994, and
predicted that the volume of its annual trade will soon reach
4,000 million.
</P>
<P>
The organization was founded in 1994 on the basis of the
Preferential Trade Area for the Eastern and Southern Africa
(PTA),
</P>
<P>
To facilitate intra-COMESA trade, the COMESA has among other
things adopted a program to gradually reduce and eventually
eliminate tariffs and other charges for eligible products traded
among the member countries by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
So far the implementation of the program has been successful
with most of the 20 member countries having reduced their
tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Comoros, Uganda and Madagascar have reduced tariffs by 80
percent, Kenya, Malawi, Mauritius, Sudan, Zimbabwe, Eritrean and
Tanzania by 70 percent and Zambia, Burundi and Rwanda by 60
percent, while three other countries have been exempted till
1998.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA will also eliminate non-tariff barriers to the
inter-regional trade, simplify and harmonize trade documents and
procedures as well as liberalize and streamline the rules of
origin.
</P>
<P>
One of the biggest obstacles to the growth of trade among
COMESA member countries is lack of information about exports and
imports of each country.
</P>
<P>
To solve this problem, the regional organization identifies
and lists products available in each member state for export to
others and disseminates the information to the business
community.
</P>
<P>
After undertaking demand and supply surveys, the COMESA
secretariat, in collaboration with the national chambers of
commerce and industry and national export promotion agencies of
the member countries, organizes meetings between buyers and
sellers for each specific product, and meetings among producers,
exporters and importers of a particular product, thus providing
information about this product and enabling them to make deals.
</P>
<P>
All the buyers and sellers meetings have resulted in doing
business. For example, the meeting held in Harare, Zimbabwe in
1989 generated 70 million U.S. Dollars worth of business.
</P>
<P>
A trade information network has been established since 1987.
It involves the establishment of trade information units, which
are provided with computers free of charge in which trade
information is coordinated at the COMESA secretariat in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the COMESA regularly organizes two kinds of trade
fairs -- general trade fairs and specialized trade fairs.
</P>
<P>
So far five general trade fairs and two specialized trade
fairs have been organized with a total of about 800 million
Dollars worth of business negotiated and contracted.
</P>
<P>
To speed up movement of transit traffic in the region, the
COMESA has introduced a regional road customs transit declaration
document to replace the 13 documents used in the past.
</P>
<P>
The simplified document has reduced costs, delays, pilferages
and breakages which previously added to the cost of intra-COMESA
trade.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the COMESA is striving to create a regional single
market and have a single currency by the year 2020. If the
timetable is not derailed, there could be free movement of goods,
services, labor and capital within the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
