<HEADLINE> European Shares up on Stronger Dollar, Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
continued their recent recovery and all closed sharply higher
Wednesday, supported by Wall Street's advances and a stronger
dollar.
</P>
<P>
British shares on the London market closed comfortably firmer
on the back of the Dow's advances for the past three sessions
although the FTSE 100 index failed to regain the 4,300 level,
ending 23.0 points higher at 4,292.3.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that stronger international bond markets boosted
market sentiment, while latest US industrial production data gave
hopes for a subdued inflationary outlook.
</P>
<P>
However, it was believed that uncertainty over Britain's May 1
general election and worries about higher interest rates to curb
inflationary pressures would limit the market's near-term upside
potential.
</P>
<P>
The Frankfurt market, which had suffered heavy losses last
week, also closed higher on the back of firmer bonds and dollar
strength, which is favorable for exports, with the DAX-30 index
29.7 points up at 3,359.46.
</P>
<P>
Analysts expected the upward trend to continue in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
Shares on the Paris bourse made the strongest gains among the
three major European markets, underpinned by French bonds,
although the CAC-40 index drifted off the day's high, ending up
38.55 points at 2,617.55, a rise of 1.49 percent on the day.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of leading British shares ended up 23.0
points at 4,292.3. The Frankfurt DAX-30 index closed 29.7 points
higher at 3,359.46. In Paris, the CAC-40 index finished 38.55
points firmer at 2,617.55.  
</P>
</TEXT>
