<HEADLINE> UN Council Suspends Reduction of Macedonia Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED Nations, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
decided on Wednesday to suspend a reduction of the military
component of the U.N. Preventive Deployment Force (UNPREDEP) in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
In a unanimously adopted resolution, the council also welcomed
the redeployment of UNPREDEP already achieved in the light of the
situation in Albania, and encouraged the U.N. secretary-general to
continue further redeployment of UNPREDEP taking into
consideration the situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Last December, under the suggestion of former Secretary-General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali, the council decided to reduce the
1050-member force to 750 by April 1. The reduction process began
in March.
</P>
<P>
But recent developments in Albania and the resulting situation
of lawlessness and banditry in certain parts of that country have
demonstrated that stability in the Balkan region remains extremely
fragile.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Security Council, Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said that proceeding with the planned reduction during a
period when further regional instability continues to be a
possibility could put at risk the credibility of the international
community's first serious effort at preventive deployment.
</P>
<P>
He recommended that the Security Council approve the suspension
of the reduction of the UNPREDEP military component until the end
of the current mandate on May 31, 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
